<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Post-ChristmasShopping     12-26 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Post-Christmas Shopping,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bargain Hunters Jam Malls In After-Christmas Shopping Stampede</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Shoppers with visions of after-Christmas sales dancing in their
heads jammed malls across the nation Monday as gifts were traded
from California to New Jersey, but Boston's famed bargain basement
wasn't booming.
   The day after Christmas is one of the biggest shopping days of
the year, and this year, retailers reveled in a happy coincidence
that gave most people the day off to return gifts and swarm around
sale tables.
   ``It's packed, it'll be maxed out today,'' said Lora Dubbs,
manager of the 269-store Galleria in the Los Angeles suburb of
Glendale. The mall's department stores opened two hours early, at 8
a.m., she said.
   In San Diego County, dressing-room lines were so long at the
Nordstrom's department store in the North County Fair mall that men
took their bargain duds to the men's restroom to try on.
   In Indiana, stores were packed with shoppers looking for deals
and returning gifts that weren't quite right. Returns increase at
least tenfold the day after Christmas, said Rod Rumrill, manager of
the Brownsburg K mart.
   In Minnesota, consumers were welcome to make returns with few
questions asked, said George Hite, a spokesman for Target Stores, in
Minneapolis.
   Returned items ranged from clothing to telephone answering
machines, Hite said.
   ``What happens (with answering machines) is people realize
nobody's calling them,'' said Hite. ``We get a lot back.''
   New Jersey shoppers lined up early at stores to return Christmas
gifts and to take advantage of sales in the post-Yuletide rush.
   ``This is one of the biggest shopping days of the year _ tied
with Thanksgiving,'' said Mary Kitsos, assistant mall manager at the
Bergen Mall in Paramus.
   In Michigan, consumers looking for a better fit kept some stores
busy.
   ``Those misfit gifts are coming back,'' said Randy Boadway,
manager at Meijer's Thrifty Acres, in Northville.
   ``Crazy,'' is how K mart employee Lynn Berglund described the
activity at a store in Kingsford. Most people seemed to be sweeping
up holiday items at bargain prices, Berglund said. Wrapping paper
was most popular.
   But in Boston, cashiers at Filene's Basement looked disappointed
when the expected crowds failed to materialize at the famed bargain
mecca by noon Monday.
   ``I kind of look forward to them,'' said Nelda Scott, referring
to the traditional post-holiday shopping crowd. ``It can be fun if
the customers are nice.''
   Store clerks said that the confusion over store hours Monday may
have contributed to the lesser turnout. A judge ruled last week
against retailers who sought permission to open all day Monday.
   Although Filene's and other stores around Boston's Downtown
Crossing appeared quieter than normal, other shopping malls in the
region reported good turnouts.
   ``The stores picked up around noon,'' said Beth Chase, a clerk at
Bloomingdale's at the Chestnut Hill Mall. ``I think a lot of people
got up late, had brunch and then went shopping.''
   But some store managers already had their minds on other holiday
happiness to sell.
   ``Valentine's Day goes up tomorrow,'' said Joann DeMilner,
manager of Gala's Hallmark in suburban Detroit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 2358EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CondoKid     12-26 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Condo Kid,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Plans Fight To Keep Girl In Adults-Only Condo Complex</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARGATE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On school days, 9-year-old Jamie Swartz
takes her lunchbox and books and joins the world of children. She
giggles with her classmates and makes drawings for display on the
family refrigerator.
   And then she returns to a world of adult rules where she is not
welcome.
   The adults-only condominium where she moved in to live with her
father as her mother lay dying of cancer has become an unfriendly
place following the condo board's decision to force the child off
the premises by Jan. 10.
   The impact of the Viewpointe condominium board's order has
spilled beyond the cream-colored stucco buildings that overlook a
man-made pond and the rear of the shopping center in this inland
community 30 miles north of Miami.
   In Florida, second only to Hawaii in the number of condo
dwellers, the girl's plight has rallied critics of ``condo
commandos'' who zealously enforce their rules.
   Attorneys and condominium directors are watching the controversy
with interest; a federal anti-discrimination housing law outlawing
many adults-only communities is set to take effect in March.
   ``I understand the perception this case has,'' said Douglas
Neway, an attorney representing the Viewpointe board. ``But the rule
is `no children' and they have a right to enforce that rule.''
   ``This place is run like the Gestapo,'' said Jamie's stepmother,
Jill Swartz. ``You can always make an exception.''
   The girl's stepmother and father, Lynn, are seeking a buyer for
the two-bedroom condominium while the board threatens to begin
eviction proceedings.
   So far there have been no bids for the $56,000 unit, which the
couple purchased three years ago for about $50,000.
   ``I think the publicity has hurt us. Who wants to buy a place
where they think the neighbors don't try to work with you?'' said
Ms. Swartz.
   Jamie moved into the complex in April after her 42-year-old
mother, Maye Swartz, was hospitalized with cancer. The condo board
voted in July to allow Jamie to stay until her mother finished
chemotherapy. She died in September.
   As the Jan. 10 deadline nears, the Swartzes are preparing to
fight.
   ``We can't afford to pay a mortgage on two homes,'' said Ms.
Swartz. ``If we ever want to get a little house on a street with
children for Jamie, then we can't walk away from this place.
   ``Believe me, we'd like to leave,'' said Ms. Swartz, who doesn't
allow the girl to talk to reporters. ``Jamie walks through the
complex and no one will talk to her. She's been brave, but it's
still rough for a little girl who's been through what she has.''
   Many of the Swartzes' neighbors were sympathetic to the family's
dilemma, but none would give their name for fear of irritating the
condo board, whose members are elected from the complex.
   ``She's a quiet little girl who doesn't bother anyone,'' said a
woman living next door. ``What ever happened to helping people out
in time of crisis? I guess that's old-fashioned.''
   If a court battle ensues, several factors are working in the
couple's favor, said Harvey Koppell, an attorney who offered free
assistance to the Swartzes.
   Koppell said the Viewpointe bylaws allow exemptions from the
adults-only rule. In addition, the condo board may be forced to
accept Jamie when the federal Fair Housing Amendment Act takes
effect March 12.
   The new provisions ban age discrimination with the exception of
subsidized facilities for the elderly, or in complexes where all
occupants are 62 or older or if 80 percent of the units have one
resident at least 55 years old.
   ``I don't think they are even close to meeting one of the
exemptions,'' said Koppell.
   Neway said he believes the complex may fulfill the 55-year-old
exemption, but no surveys have been taken.
   The concept of adults-only living is well accepted in Florida,
where legions of retirees seek friends their own age and a respite
from the noise of children.
   But fears from some condo directors that the Swartzes' stalemate
will be replayed elsewhere may be unwarranted, said attorney Gary
Poliakoff, author of ``The Law of Condominium Operations.''
   ``Retirement communities are generally built in areas not near
schools and other services,'' said Poliakoff, whose Fort Lauderdale
firm represents 1,600 condo associations across the country. ``There
are no facilities designed for children. How many families do you
think will want to live in an adult-only setting?''
   Some who have chosen to fight the adults-only trend in Florida
have lost. In 1977, a couple was forced out of their Tamarac
condominium after having a baby. The unsuccessful age discrimination
suit went as far as the Florida Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
