<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChildMortality     12-26 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Mortality,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Not-Very-Merry Holiday Season For Some Children</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Pan Am flight 103 crashed last week,
claiming more than 280 lives, the reaction was one of virtual
universal horror. But the death toll was only a small fraction of
the number of children under 5 who die almost unnoticed each day
from hunger and disease.
   If Christmas Day was typical, about 38,300 such children from
poor countries died, according to new estimates released by the
United Nation's Children's Fund.
   Put another way, the death toll from the Pan Am flight is equaled
every 10 minutes or so in terms of children aged 5 and under.
   These figures are derived from UNICEF's calculation that 14
million children under age 5 died in 1987, partly because so many
countries in Latin America, Asia and Africa, impoverished by debt
and other factors, are cutting back on social services.
   UNICEF executive director James Grant said last week that 3
million of these children died last year ``because they didn't have
50 cents worth of vaccine in them.''
   The situation apparently has changed little and may have even
worsened in 1988. The World Bank reported last week that poorer
countries are transferring their wealth to richer nations at record
levels this year _ 50 percent higher than 1987.
   The bank said the 17 most highly indebted countries of the Third
World will give wealthy countries $31.1 billion more than they
receive, triple the amount of 1983. Crushing debt repayments mean
less money left over for imports of basic human necessities such as
food and medicine.
   No region has been harder hit than Latin America, where per
capita income is 8 percent below 1980 levels.
   The Inter-American Dialogue, a gathering of concerned citizens
from throughout the hemisphere, said in a recent report the social
consequences of Latin America's prolonged depression have been
multiplying.
   ``The people of Latin America have seen their wages fall and
their jobs disappear; their housing, schools, hospitals and other
public services have deteriorated; and they have endured food
shortages and mounting street crime.
   ``Financially strapped governments have been unable to address
such fundamental social problems as the vast gap between rich and
poor, the deep poverty of rural areas and city slums, widespread
malnutrition and high rates of infant mortality,'' the report said.
   President-elect Bush seems to be aware of the problems that the
$1.3 trillion debt burden is causing Third World countries. Since
his election, Bush has met with the presidents of Mexico and
Argentina and the incoming president of Venezuela _ all countries
where foreign debt is a major political and economic issue.
   Two days before release of the UNICEF report, Bush left the
impression that his administration is likely to ask commercial banks
to ease the debt burden of developing countries.
   Bush said the issue ``should be subject to a major review which
will include not just the Treasury but our national security people
because we've got enormous problems, particularly in our own
hemisphere, on Third World debt.''
   U.S. policy on the debt issue was spelled out in September 1985
by then Treasury Secretary and now Secretary of State-designate
James A. Baker III.
   His proposals for restoring growth in Latin America and elsewhere
call for a combination of economic reforms in the debtor countries
and new public and private lending to meet their capital needs.
   But, as the Inter-American Dialogue report points out, Latin
American governments have lost confidence in the Baker approach
because it has not produced the resources it promised.
   ``Many now see debt relief _ to reduce the region's financial
obligations and massive capital outflows _ as the only way for Latin
America to escape its economic bind,'' the report said.
   To UNICEF's Grant, the link between debt and child mortality is
obvious. He said that in 16 of the most debt-burdened countries, the
number of childhood deaths in the last 12 months is approximately
650,000 more than would have been the case if the 1970-80 rate of
decline in under-5 mortality had continued.
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for the
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 0036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WaterTransfers-Texts     12-26 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Transfers-Texts,830</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Interior Department's
policy statement supporting sales of federally provided water in the
West, together with the text of the 1986 draft of the policy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Primacy in water allocation and management decisions rests
principally with the states. Voluntary water transactions under this
policy must be in accordance with applicable state and federal laws.
   The Department of the Interior (DOI) will become involved in
facilitating a proposed voluntary water transaction only when it can
be accomplished without diminution of service to those parties
otherwise being served by such federal resources, and when:
   (a) there is an existing federal contractual or other legal
obligation associated with the water supply; or
   (b) there is an existing water right held by the federal
government that may be affected by the transaction; or
   (c) it is proposed to use federally owned storage or conveyance
capacity to facilitate the transaction; or
   (d) the proposed transaction will affect federal project
operations; and
   (e) the appropriate state, tribal, or other non-federal political
authorities or subdivisions request DOI's active involvement.
   DOI will participate in or approve transactions when there are no
adverse third-party consequences, or when such third-party
consequences will be heard and adjudicated in appropriate state
forums, or when such consequences will be mitigated to the
satisfaction of the affected parties.
   As a general rule, DOI's role will be to facilitate transactions
that are in accordance with applicable state and federal law and
proposed by others. In doing so, DOI will consider the positions of
the affected state, tribal, and local authorities. DOI will not
suggest a specific transaction except when it is part of an Indian
water rights settlement, a solution to a water rights controversy,
or when it may provide a dependable water supply the provision of
which otherwise would involve the expenditure of federal funds. Such
a suggestion would not be carried out without the concurrence of all
affected non-federal parties.
   The fact that the transaction may involve the use of water
supplies developed by federal water resource projects shall not be
considered during evaluation of a proposed transaction.
   One of DOI's objectives will be to ensure that the federal
government is in an acceptable financial, operational and
contractual position following accomplishment of a transaction under
this policy. Unless required explicitly by existing law, contracts
or regulations, DOI will refrain from burdening the transaction with
additional costs, fees or charges, except for those costs actually
incurred by DOI in performance of its functions in a particular
transaction.
   DOI will consider, in cooperation with appropriate state, tribal
and local authorities, necessary measures that may be required to
mitigate any adverse environmental impacts that may arise as a
result of the proposed transaction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Here is the 1986 statement that was never issued:
   Primacy in water allocation and management decisions relating to
voluntary exchanges of water is reaffirmed to rest with the states.
   Federal reclamation laws do not preclude support for and
implementation of a voluntary water exchange policy. When voluntary
water exchanges are proposed, they will be viewed in a positive
manner. If project authorizing legislation is in direct conflict,
changes in project authorizing legislation will be supported if
project purposes can be protected or changed to meet current
conditions while protecting or compensating third parties.
   The Bureau of Reclamation needs to become involved in
facilitating voluntary water exchanges only if: (a) there is an
existing federal contractual obligation associated with the water;
(b) there is a proposed use of federal storage-conveyance capacity;
(c) the proposed action will affect existing federal project
operations; or (d) the appropriate state or other non-federal
authority requests reclamation's active involvement.
   If existing water service or repayment contracts need to be
revised to comply with this policy and the proposed water exchange,
those changes will be made in a routine and expeditious manner,
provided such changes are consistent with federal reclamation law
and meet the policy requirements listed herein.
   While voluntary exchanges within state or within basin boundaries
will be more easily approved, exchanges involving a larger
geographic area also will be considered.
   Short-term and long-term water exchanges will be supported.
Short-term water exchanges are defined as having an exchange life of
no more than one year. The contractual obligations associated with
this water will remain with the entity currently responsible.
Long-term water exchanges are defined as having an exchange life of
more than one year. The contractual obligations associated with this
water may be transferred, through negotiated contracts, to the
responsible entity receiving the water. Any additional costs
associated with the transfer, including any power interference
charge, shall be advanced or repaid in a manner negotiated by the
parties involved.
   Exchanges may involve changes in type, location, or priority of
use. All exchanges must be in accordance with applicable state and
federal laws, including the protection of the water rights of those
who are not direct parties to the exchange.
   The United States' interest in project repayment will be fully
protected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 0040EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Homeless-Housing     12-26 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless-Housing,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slow Movement on Law Ordering Feds To Lease Unused Buildings To
Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Grate Life Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Square 571'' is the name given by the
government to a 43,000-square-foot federal building that sits vacant
in the middle of the District of Columbia, footsteps away from a
homeless shelter which lately has been turning away 50 to 75 people
a night.
   A law passed in mid-1987 directed the federal government to make
its ``underutilized'' property available to the homeless, but Square
571 was beyond the grasp of homeless advocates.
   The reason: The federal government interpreted ``underutilized''
to mean partially occupied, not vacant.
   Under that reading of the law, only 12 of the U.S. government's
properties _ Uncle Sam owns 429,959 buildings and 727 million acres
of land _ were deemed suitable for the homeless.
   Of those, two _ a post office in Lynn, Mass., and an office
building in Bell, Calif. _ have actually been devoted to that
purpose since passage of the McKinney Homeless Assistance Act in
July 1987.
   These facts outrage homeless advocates, who have sued the
government to force it to make more of its underused and unused
properties available.
   On Sept. 30, U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch ruled in the
advocates' favor, noting ``it's unreasonable to suggest that
Congress chose to lease to the homeless half-empty properties and
properties which are used part of the time, but no properties which
are wholly unoccupied.''
   ``Pitifully few of the numerous unused federal properties are
being evaluated for their suitability to assist the homeless,''
Gasch wrote in the decision. ``Those that are found to be suitable
are not being made available to homeless providers.''
   Gasch forbade the federal government from selling or transferring
any of its excess or surplus properties until it has complied with
the law.
   Currently, the government has 335 excess or surplus properties
ranging from a three-story federal office building in downtown
Providence, R.I., to a vacant school in Phoenix.
   Excess property is defined as that which isn't needed by the
government agency which controls it, while surplus property isn't
needed by any federal agency at all, according to Earl Jones,
commissioner of the General Services Administration's property
resources service. Normally, when a piece of federal property is
declared excess, it is turned in to the GSA, which can offer it to
other federal agencies or state or local governments, or sell it on
the open market, Jones said.
   Two months after Gasch's ruling, no more federal properties had
been leased to the homeless and the parties to the lawsuit went back
to court. The National Coalition for the Homeless asked for a
timetable for the government to comply, charging that the Department
of Housing and Urban Development was trying to stall.
   Gasch has given the government until Wednesday to review half its
335 surplus and excess properties to determine suitability for the
homeless, and until Jan. 12 to assess the other half. If it doesn't
finish on time, Gasch could find the government in contempt.
   Asked what the government had been doing in the two months since
the judge's initial ruling, James Stimson, the assistant on homeless
policy to the secretary of HUD, said officials were ``reviewing the
list'' and revising the criteria for deciding which properties would
be suitable for the homeless.
   ``There've been no major changes,'' he said. ``Some additional
factors were added recently.''
   Those factors were to allow for exclusions of properties in flood
plains or near hazardous or toxic waste sites or near explosive
materials, he said.
   ``I find that an example of exercise in the absurd, spending two
months to make that change,'' said Maria Foscarinis, attorney for
the National Coalition for the Homeless. ``They wasted over two
months, as far as I can tell.''
   Foscarinis said she believed the government was looking for ways
to exclude more of the properties on the list and was only prevented
from coming up with more loopholes because ``they were subjected to
very close scrutiny by a congressional committee and by us.''
   Stimson denied the allegation.
   Stimson said HUD had identified three properties on the list of
335 suitable for the homeless and two unsuitable. GSA had
recommended that HUD look at those particular properties because
they might fit the bill, Stimson admitted.
   Those that were deemed suitable were: the John Fogarty Federal
Building in Providence, which is partially occupied; a federal
building in Smithfield, N.C., which is fully occupied by the
Department of Agriculture; and about five acres of land known as the
Raritan Depot in New Jersey.
   Those that were excluded: a group of buildings at Fort Hayes in
Columbus, Ohio, because they are structurally unsound, and a former
missile testing site in Dade, Fla., because it's in a flood plain.
   Those recommendations have been sent back to the GSA, Stimson
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
