<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 0042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Crash-CIA     12-26 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-CIA,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Says CIA Passenger, Alone, Would Not Have Prompted Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vice-chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee says the possible presence of a CIA operative on the Pan
Am jet that crashed last week probably would not, by itself, have
provoked a terrorist attack.
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said Sunday on ABC's ``This Week
With David Brinkley'' that he could not confirm whether the CIA
agent had been on the flight.
   But Cohen said that even if the agent had been aboard it would
not necessarily be significant because terrorists ``could have
eliminated him'' by direct assassination on the ground.
   ``I don't think you can draw any connection one way or another at
this point,'' Cohen said.
   The FBI's executive assistant director, Oliver Revell, on Sunday
denied earlier reports that the CIA's station chief in Beirut,
Lebanon, was aboard the Pan Am jumbo jet that crashed last week in
Scotland. He declined to say, however, whether any other CIA
operatives were on the plane.
   ``We cannot comment on intelligence community personnel, but I am
authorized to say that the station chief in Beirut was not on that
aircraft,'' he said in an interview with CBS Radio.
   Two government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, had
said Saturday that the CIA's chief in Beirut was among the 258
people aboard the aircraft.
   Contacted again Sunday, one of the officials reiterated to The
Associated Press that the station chief, who has not been publicly
identified, had been a passenger on Pam Am Flight 103. Investigators
are viewing the crash as the possible result of sabotage.
   Revell was interviewed by CBS reporter Lesley Stahl following his
appearance with Stahl on the network's ``Face the Nation.'' There
was no discussion of this aspect of the crash on the television
program.
   In the post-program interview, Revell was asked whether any U.S.
government employee from Beirut had been aboard the ill-fated flight.
   ``Yes,'' he replied, ``the regional security officer from the
State Department was on the aircraft, unfortunately.''
   On Friday, the State Department said that three of its people
were on Flight 103: Matthew K. Gannon of Orange, Calif.; Ronald
Lariviere of Holyoke, Mass.; and Daniel E. O'Connor of Boston.
   Gannon was identified by the department as a political officer at
the U.S. Embassy in Beirut. The others were identified as security
officers _ Lariviere in Beirut, O'Connor in Nicosia, Cyprus.
   CIA agents frequently use embassy positions as covers for their
operations overseas.
   Revell said investigators are pursuing at least three possible
causes for the crash: a bomb planted by terrorists; a bomb placed
aboard by someone acting on a personal level wanting to kill a
particular passenger; and structural breakup of the aircraft.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
