<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PenneyAwards     12-26 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Penney Awards,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University of Missouri Announces Journalism Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter for the San Francisco Examiner
won first place for reporting in the J.C. Penney-University of
Missouri Newspaper Awards.
   Joan Smith of the Examiner won for a story on how Indian-American
children are taken from their families. She and the other winners in
the annual contest were chosen from among more than 1,400 entries,
said James D. Atwater, University of Missouri journalism dean.
   The awards announced Saturday will be presented during the
contest's annual workshop at Missouri from April 1-6.
   Other winners were:
   For reporting excellence: honorable mention to Roger Roy, The
Orlando (Fla.) Sentinel; series-special section award to Doug Heuck,
The Pittsburgh Press.
   The Sentinel won for a profile of a Tampa, Fla., man who was
paroled after serving 20 years for a double murder. Heuck won for a
story on the homeless, called ``A Reporter's Odyssey: I Am
Homeless.''
   For consumer affairs reporting: Teresa Blossom, David Everett and
John Gallagher, the Detroit Free Press; special award to feature
staff at The Boston Phoenix.
   For fashion and clothing reporting: Sally Cragin, The Boston
Phoenix.
   For health and nutrition reporting: Alex Beasley and Tim Povtak,
The Orlando (Fla.) Sentinel; special award to Claudia Morain, San
Jose Mercury News; special award to Marian Burros, The New York
Times.
   For lifestyle sections and their editors:
   Circulation less than 10,000: first place to Jane Meyer, Mercer
Island (Wash.) Reporter; second place to Ray Stephens and David
Stump, Jackson Hole (Wyo.) Guide; third place to Carol A. Azizian,
Troy Eccentric, Rochester, Mich.
   Circulation from 10,000 to 25,000: honorable mention to Barbara
Scheutz, Columbia (Mo.) Daily Tribune; honorable mention to Leigh
Hopper, The Brazosport Facts, Clute, Texas.
   Circulation 25,000 to 50,000: first place to Lynn Kinney,
Gwinnett Daily News, Lawrenceville, Ga.; second place to Lineta
Pritchard, The Sun News, Myrtle Beach, S.C.; third place to Dan
Shyrock, Times-Advocate, Escondido, Calif.; honorable mention to
Ricardo Gandara, Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune.
   Circulation 50,000 to 100,000: first place to Jim Godbold, The
Register-Guard, Eugene, Ore.; second place to Carolyn West, Daily
Press, Newport News, Va.
   Circulation 100,000 to 200,000: first place to Sandra Shea, The
Boston Phoenix; Michael Lacey, Deborah Block and Christine Tschopp,
New Times, Phoenix, Ariz.; Alan McConagha, The Washington Times.
   Circulation more than 200,000: first place to Susan S. Wyland,
The Detroit News; second place to John Brownell, Los Angeles Times;
third place to Bob Ostmann and Richard Cheverton, The Orange County
(Calif.) Register.
</TEXT>
