<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Willman     12-26 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Willman,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tony-Winning Director Dead of Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noel Willman, who won a Tony Award for directing
the 1961 Broadway production of ``A Man for All Seasons,'' has died.
He was 70.
   Willman, whose home was in New York, died of a heart attack
Saturday.
   The Northern Ireland-born Willman first appeared on Broadway in
``Legend of Lovers'' in 1951. He played Lord Byron in the 1954 film
``Beau Brummell,'' which starred Elizabeth Taylor and Peter Ustinov.
   His reputation took off in 1961 when he directed ``A Man for All
Seasons'' in London and on Broadway. He said he turned to directing
on the advice of his mentor, Tyrone Guthrie.
   In 1962, Willman staged S.J. Perelman's ``The Beauty Part,''
featuring Bert Lahr. Four years later, he directed ``A Lion in
Winter'' with Robert Preston and Rosemary Harris on Broadway.
   Willman's directorial swan songs were two limited engagements by
Katharine Hepburn in New York _ ``A Matter of Gravity'' in 1975 and
``West Side Waltz'' in 1981.
   Willman is survived by a sister.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
