<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Noel Willman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noel Willman, who won a Tony Award for directing
the 1961 Broadway production of ``A Man for All Seasons,'' died of a
heart attack Saturday. He was 70.
   Willman, whose home was in New York, was born in Londonderry,
Northern Ireland.
   He first appeared on Broadway in ``Legend of Lovers'' in 1951. He
played Lord Byron in the 1954 film ``Beau Brummell,'' which starred
Elizabeth Taylor and Peter Ustinov.
   His reputation took off in 1961 when he directed ``A Man for All
Seasons'' in London and on Broadway.
   In 1962, Willman staged S.J. Perelman's ``The Beauty Part,''
featuring Bert Lahr. Four years later, he directed ``A Lion in
Winter'' with Robert Preston and Rosemary Harris on Broadway.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Paul Horowitz</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Horowitz, a sports writer and
editor, died Sunday of a heart attack. He was 83.
   Horowitz reported on sports for the Newark Evening News from the
1930s until it folded in 1972. He was the sports editor of Stars &
Stripes' European edition during World War II.
   During his senior year of college, Horowitz was named the
outstanding baseball player at Syracuse University in New York.
</TEXT>
