<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 0103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LegsDiamond     12-26 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Legs Diamond,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Reworked `Legs Diamond' Battles Its Way To Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly two months, ``Legs Diamond'' has been
the talk of Broadway, even though the lavish Peter Allen musical
hasn't officially opened. The conversation hasn't been encouraging.
   The show about the notorious New York gangster, played by Allen,
finally premieres tonight after endless previews, two postponements
and a major overhaul that its producers hope will save the $5
million musical.
   ``We just want to make it work,'' said Arthur Rubin, one of the
show's producers, a group that also includes the Nederlander theater
organization and New York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner. ``I
didn't care how many times we had to postpone. We would do it until
we got it right.''
   ``Getting it right'' has meant making drastic changes in front of
difficult, demanding New York audiences. Because of the show's
elaborate sets, the producers bypassed an out-of-town tryout in
favor of preview performances in New York. After all, Allen, who
also wrote the show's book and lyrics, had had successes in New York
with his revues on Broadway and at Radio City Music Hall.
   So much attention has focused on ``Legs Diamond'' because it is
the only musical of Broadway's meager fall season. That fact enabled
the show to accumulate a $10 million advance, mostly from theater
parties.
   ``Legs Diamond'' is also an American musical, a home-grown
product with a highly visible star and creator.
   The previews, which originally were slated to start Oct. 18 at
the Mark Hellinger Theater, were delayed a week because of technical
problems with the mammoth and complicated sets.
   The first preview ran more than three hours. Many theatergoers
walked out after the first act. It was a scene repeated during most
early previews.
   ``The audience reaction was not too great,'' Rubin recalled
diplomatically. ``There were a lot of things to fix.''
   ``I didn't need anybody to tell me,'' said director Robert Allan
Ackerman. ``I had a very clear picture of what was wrong.''
   The opening, scheduled for Dec. 1, was postponed first to Dec. 11
and then to Dec. 26.
   Once previews were under way, Ackerman developed what amounted to
a weekly game plan to improve the musical. He would meet with author
Harvey Fierstein, choreographer Alan Johnson, and Allen _ usually
after the Sunday matinee _ and decide what they wanted to accomplish
in terms of rewrites.
   On Monday, the company's day off, Fierstein and Ackerman would do
the rewrites. On Tuesday, the company would rehearse the new
material and as much as possible of it would go into the show that
night. On Wednesday, the company would play two shows. On Thursday,
the company would learn more new material and play it that night and
throughout the weekend. On Sunday, the cycle would begin again.
   ``The part that is the most frustrating is that invariably we
would know that on Tuesday we would be unraveling the whole thing
again,'' Ackerman said. ``But each change we did made the show
better. We could feel the show getting better and better.''
   The fix involved cutting some 45 minutes from the show,
eliminating characters, throwing out sets and songs and writing and
staging an entirely new opening number, ``When I Get My Name in
Lights,'' which features Allen atop a huge electric sign announcing
the show's title. The changes boosted production costs from $4.2
million to $5.1 million.
   Among the characters jettisoned were Legs Diamond's wife and
brother, played by Christine Andreas and Bob Stillman.
   ``Nobody was let go because they weren't doing a wonderful job,''
Ackerman said. ``I think the remarkable thing about this whole
process is that we have gone through what is regarded as the most
hellish thing you can live through in the theater _ the making of a
musical _ and there has been no animosity at all.''
   For Allen, the previews were incredibly difficult, Rubin said.
``There was a lot of pressure,'' the producer added. ``He was
performing, rehearsing, and trying to write a new song, all at the
same time.''
   Major changes were stopped a week ago to give the cast time to
play the same material.
   ``I hope we fixed it all,'' Ackerman said. ``I can tell you now
that the audience reaction is tremendous, and people are really
loving. But whether or not it will be a hit, I don't know.''
</TEXT>
