<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HatboxBaby     12-26 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hatbox Baby,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman was `Hatbox Baby' Found in Desert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't until more than half a century later
that a retired aerospace worker learned she was the ``Hatbox Baby,''
a newborn found in a hatbox in the Arizona desert on Christmas Eve
1931.
   ``Everybody in my family knew the story except me,'' said Sharon
Elliott, who at age 57 still has the same red hair and blue eyes
that won so many hearts in 1931 when the story hit the newspapers.
   ``My mother didn't want me to find out. It was such a shock after
all these years _ I couldn't believe that during all that time it
had been kept from me,'' she said in an interview published Sunday
in The Mesa Tribune.
   The tale of the baby began when Edward and Julie Stewart were
making their way toward Phoenix. A puncture forced them to stop
along the dusty highway about 10 miles west of Superior.
   As Stewart repaired the tire, his wife heard a cry and then
beckoned her husband to venture with her into the desert stillness.
   A hundred yards from the road, they found a black pasteboard
hatbox with the lid fastened. Stewart kicked it, eliciting another
cry.
   The Stewarts opened the box, and inside they found an infant
about a week old, wrapped in flowered pajamas.
   Newspapers rejoiced in the incredible good fortune that led the
Stewarts to the ``hatbox baby,'' and they cooed over the red-haired,
blue-eyed waif who was eventually put up for adoption.
   Ms. Elliott, a retired aerospace worker who moved from California
to Mesa several months ago, learned she was the hatbox baby about
two years ago, shortly before her adoptive mother passed away.
   ``My daughter and son-in-law were being transferred to Mesa, and
my mother was afraid that somehow I would find out _ that somebody
would say something and I would get hurt. It was a big story in
those days, and for years the papers wrote about it every Christmas,
wondering whatever happened to that little baby.
   ``When she told me, I cried. She was the only mother I ever knew,
the only one I ever wanted. But now that she's gone, I'd like to
find out more.''
   Arizona newspapers followed the baby's story closely until she
was adopted in February 1932. Years later, newspapers and national
Sunday magazines repeatedly asked whatever became of the baby.
   ``She now is 30 years old and quietly beautiful, they say, a
woman of exceptional grace and purity living somewhere in Arizona,''
columnist Don Dedera wrote in The Arizona Republic, on Christmas
Day, 1961.
   Dedera wrote many more columns and stories about the baby, hoping
someday she might read one and come forward.
   ``It's such an intriguing little mystery, a wonderful story,''
Dedera, now a freelance writer, said in a recent interview. I always
had hoped I'd be able to wrap it up.''
   Ms. Elliott eventually went to The Mesa Tribune and identified
herself as the hatbox baby to see if reporters had any information
about who left her in the desert and why. But nothing about her
origin has surfaced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
