<DOCNO> AP881226-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 0135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Tower     12-26 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tower,254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tower Hopes to Cut Use of Military Personnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush's choice to lead the
Defense Department says an emphasis on weapons systems that depend
on fewer people may help the Pentagon meet its needs in a time of
budgetary constraint.
   ``The big cost is not in the B-2 (bomber), the B-1 and the
aircraft carriers,'' former Texas Sen. John Tower said Sunday. ``The
big cost is not in the hardware, the big cost is in personnel.''
   Tower, Bush's designated defense secretary, said one of his first
priorities would be devising a strategy to achieve national
objectives for defense.
   ``Then we have to look at the roles and missions of all our
forces and see where they fit into that strategy,'' he said on the
CBS-TV program ``Face the Nation.''
   Programs that don't fit, Tower said, ``get low priority and they
get cut. And hopefully, by going to less manpower-intensive systems
we can make some economies.''
   Tower was long rumored as Bush's choice for defense secretary but
the announcement was delayed for several weeks as the FBI conducted
an exhaustive background check of the former senator, known for his
pro-defense positions while in the Congress.
   ``I discovered much to my dismay that not everybody loves me,''
Tower said when asked about the lengthy review, fueled in part by
accusations made by his ex-wife.
   Of reports that he sometimes drank to excess, Tower said he only
drank in moderation. ``I'm only a wine drinker,'' he said. ``I don't
drink spirits.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
