<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Lower, Stock Prices Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar.
Picks up 4th pvs, `Trading was ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down aginst the Japanese yen on
Monday, while share prices advanced on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 124.72 yen, down 0.23 yen from Friday's
close of 124.95 yen. After opening at 124.85 yen, the currency
ranged between 124.63 yen and 124.90 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
0.10 points during its half-day session Saturday, added another
181.65 points, or 0.61 percent, closing at 29,868.01.
   Trading was thin, but market players showed interest in
high-priced issues such as finances, which can influence the index
even if the number of shares changing hands is small, said a dealer
with Daiwa Securities.
   ``The majority of dealers were sitting on the sidelines because
they feel safer getting rid of shares before the year-end and New
Year holidays and because of uncertainties including the emperor's
condition,'' he said.
   Markets will close when Emperor Hirohito dies. Christmas Day
marked his 63rd year on the Chrysanthemum Throne, but the
87-year-old monarch has been in serious condition with internal
hemorrhaging for more than three months.
   Traders are also reluctant to make major moves in a shortened
trading week. Because of the New Year's holiday, the stock market
will be open for two full-day sessions and one half-day session this
week.
   Trading on the currency exchange was slow, reflecting the
Christmas holiday lull on overseas markets.
   ``Market players could not decide on trading tactics today
without knowing trends on overseas markets,'' said a dealer at
Mitsubishi Bank.
</TEXT>
