<DOCNO> AP881226-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 0304EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bush-HuntingTown     12-26 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Hunting Town,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Town Hopes to Capitalize on Proximity to Bush's Hunting
Retreat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEEVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This farm town is unaccustomed to being in
the national spotlight, but all that could change because a
10,000-acre spread in ``God's country'' is a favorite hunting spot
of President-elect Bush.
   The president-elect today was to begin a four-day visit to Will
Farish's Lazy F Ranch. For the past 20 Christmas seasons, Bush has
retreated there to tote a shotgun through the South Texas mesquite
in search of quail and other game birds.
   Nobody paid much attention until the vice president became the
president-elect. And some in this town of 15,000 are applauding the
change.
   ``It would bring a lot of tourists to town,'' said Janice Porter,
manager of the Beeville Chamber of Commerce. ``It would do a lot for
Beeville.''
   ``He hunts in a rough place, really, but he calls it `God's
country,''' said City Manager Jose Montez. ``I'm sure that if he
keeps coming here, we will receive some national exposure.''
   Beeville, 65 miles northwest of Corpus Christi, last saw a
president when William Howard Taft stopped by to make a whistlestop
speech in the early 1900s.
   Bush aides said the vice president would arrive and depart on Air
Force Two at the nearby Chase Field Naval Air Station, Bee County's
largest employer, with 551 civilian employees and 1,286 military
personnel.
   Downtown streets around the red-domed courthouse were being
spruced up for Bush.
   Beeville has a 2,500-student college, a two-screen movie theater,
a 12-lane bowling alley, three banks, two radio stations and just
125 motel and hotel rooms.
   It was founded in 1835 by Irish settlers and named after Bernard
E. Bee, who served in the government of the Republic of Texas, which
lasted from 1836 until Texas joined the union in 1845.
   Recently, Beeville's economy has suffered from the drop in oil
prices and lean years for farmers and ranchers. As with many other
small cities, big discount department stores on the outskirts of
town have put a squeeze on the downtown business district, where the
city has begun a $450,000 revitalization project.
   Susan Stasny, who in 1986 was elected Bee County's first
Republican county commissioner, met Bush during one of his hunting
trips. She said having a president visit occasionally would boost
the status of the city and county.
   Farish, a Houston millionaire whose ranch is just outside town,
is a longtime Bush friend whose company manages Bush's investments
through a blind trust.
</TEXT>
