<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChristmasEveCrash     12-26 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christmas Eve Crash,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Die En Route To Christmas Eve Celebration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOX, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family was opening Christmas presents when a
somber police officer showed up at the door with shocking news: six
relatives and a fiancee had been killed in a traffic accident while
on their way to the home.
   ``It was total chaos,'' said Mazel McCarty of Knox, the
great-aunt of one of the victims, 6-year-old Crystal Davis. ``It was
unreal when they told us about the accident. ... We're so
devastated. We all feel we'll wake up any minute. It's just a
nightmare.''
   Six members of the Davis family and the fiancee of one of them
were killed Saturday when their westbound car veered into the path
of an eastbound dump truck two miles southwest of this northern
Indiana town, authorities said.
   Driver Floyd Davis, 25, of Knox, had tried to avoid a car that
had slowed down to make a turn, police said.
   The victims were pronounced dead at the scene, which was littered
with Christmas presents. The driver of the truck was not seriously
hurt.
   In addition to Davis and his stepdaughter Crystal, the dead were
identified as Davis' wife, Rosalind Davis, 23; his 17-year-old
brother Jesse; his mother, Gloria, 46; his 3-year-old stepson, Carl
James Davis; and Laura Cites, 25, Jesse Davis' fiancee.
   Weather was not believed to be a factor in the crash, authorities
said.
   The family was on their way to celebrate Christmas Eve at a
relative's home near North Judson, said Starke County Coroner
Douglas E. O'Donnell.
   ``It just couldn't be worse, Cites' sister-in-law Linda Fort said
Sunday. ``People are giving this time of year, but this really puts
a damper on everything. It's still the Lord's birthday. And she is
with the Lord. That's good. That gives us a lot of comfort.''
</TEXT>
