<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Blacks     12-26 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Blacks,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Surround Buildings Housing African Students; 13 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a dozen people were injured in an
all-night clash that started at a school dance between Chinese and
African students in Nanking, the official Xinhua news agency said
today.
   Thousands of Chinese surrounded two buildings at one university
where African students live and pelted students with rocks and
bottles for seven hours, said an African student, contacted by
telephone from Beijing.
   The Chinese then marched to other universities and bombarded
other dormitories which house African students.
   The Xinhua report said two Africans and 11 Chinese employees from
Hehai University in the eastern Chinese city were injured.
   The incident was the latest in a series of violent outbreaks
between black African students and Chinese during the last several
years. Chinese authorities say they are isolated cases, and deny
charges by the Africans that they are a result of racism against
Africans in Chinese society.
   Xinhua said the problem started when two African students
escorting Chinese women to a school dance refused a request by
university authorities to register the women's names. The common
practice is designed to limit contact between Chinese and foreigners.
   The report said other African students forced open the door and
attacked university employees, teachers and students with iron
sticks, bottles and rocks.
   The African student, who was at the party, said he first learned
of a problem when rocks and bottles began flying into the dance hall.
   ``I looked outside and I saw a crowd of about 2,000 Chinese,'' he
said.
   He said the crowd threw rocks and bottles at the dance hall and
two student dormitories from about 10 p.m. Saturday until 5 a.m.
Sunday.
   ``The crowd trapped us inside the buildings and we couldn't get
out,'' said the student.
   Another band of Chinese returned to Hehai at noon Sunday and
continued throwing rocks and bottles at the building, he said.
   That crowd, which he estimated at about 4,000, then marched to
two other universities in Nanking where black Africans study. He
quoted African students there as saying the crowd also threw rocks
and bottles at African dormitories.
   In its report, Xinhua said an unspecified number of students held
a street march, shouting ``punish assailants.''
   The African student, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
police escorted about 70 African students to Nanjing's main train
station Sunday. He and Xinhua said the students demanded that they
be sent to Beijing.
   Today, a Dutch student at Nanking University said about 200 black
Africans from three different universities were at the station and
all wanted to go to Beijing. An official at the train station twice
refused to let a reporter talk by telephone to the students.
   Xinhua said local police have taken measures to protect the
African students and said some Africans have returned to the
university.
   In May 1986, about 18 Africans studying in the northeastern city
of Tianjin fled to Beijing because of reported threats from Chinese
following a bottle-throwing battle that started after Chinese
students complained of noise from a foreigners' party.
   About 200 African students in Beijing then staged a march to
protest what they said was racism against the estimated 1,500
Africans studying on Chinese campuses.
   In 1980, 19 Africans and Arabs and 24 Chinese were injured in a
fight in Shanghai that also began over loud music from a foreigner's
radio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
