<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Aid     12-26 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Aid,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0473 to fix catagory code</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Group Brings Tons Of Supplies To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Baptist minister from New Jersey who
came under Contra rebel fire this year has defied U.S. government
policy and brought about 70 tons of food, medicine and supplies to
the Nicaraguan people for Christmas.
   The Rev. Lucius Walker arrived in Nicaragua on Christmas Eve with
a caravan of 18 vehicles carrying the goods for the victims of the
seven-year civil war.
   ``This feels like a great sense of triumph, because the terrorism
(here) is supported by the government of the United States and we
are representatives of the goodwill of the people of the United
States,'' the Baptist minister said.
   Walker, of Demarest, N.J., is the executive director of the New
York-based Interreligious Foundation For Community Organization,
which sponsored the relief effort, called Pastors For Peace.
   The Reagan administration in 1985 ordered an economic boycott of
leftist Nicaragua, but the ban excludes humanitarian aid.
   In July, another convoy of aid crossed the U.S.-Mexico border
after a long dispute with U.S. Customs Service, which said taking
the trucks to Nicaragua would violate the 1985 measure.
   The government agrees the roughly 70 tons of supplies qualify as
humanitarian aid exempt from the embargo, but says the vehicles are
not aid.
   Walker's vehicles, which crossed the U.S. border on Dec. 14, were
detained briefly by customs officials, according to Tom Hansen, a
project coordinator from New York.
   ``We were forced to call our lawyers and say the licensing
request they wanted was illegal,'' he said. ``Humanitarian aid
doesn't require an export license.''
   Walker's organization is strongly opposed to the Contra rebels,
who with U.S. backing have fought since 1981 to try to oust the
Sandinistas.
   When Walker visited Nicaragua in August, he said, he was slightly
wounded by a Contra bullet fired during an attack on a riverboat in
eastern Nicaragua. But he vowed to return with aid.
   ``I feel a great sense of satisfaction and rightness,'' Walker
said.
   The goods will be distributed among Nicaraguans by religious
groups, said Sharon Haas, another project coordinator from Cleveland.
   Ms. Haas said she doesn't see much hope for a change in U.S.
policies toward the Nicaraguan government after the January
inauguaration of George Bush as president.
   Ms. Haas said the group planned to travel to the Nicaraguan
coastal city of Bluefields to see the devastation left by the Oct.
22 hurricane.
   Walker said he was wounded while traveling from Bluefields, but
rebel activity there has dropped substantially after a cease-fire
agreement was signed by the government and the Contras in March.
Talks aimed at establishing a permanent peace broke down in
September.
   Most Contras have fled to camps in Honduras, where they received
U.S.-supplied aid ranging from food to uniforms.
   Congress stopped U.S. military aid to the rebels in February but
allowed distribution of non-lethal aid to continue in neighboring
Honduras.
</TEXT>
