<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Crash-FalseAlarm     12-26 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-False Alarm,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Learns On Christmas Eve Son Didn't Die in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CASEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the worst and best of Christmases for
Jack Wittman, who thought he had lost his son in the Pan Am crash
over Scotland and then, suddenly, received the gift of his boy's
life.
   ``I had the greatest present I could have had. I had my Christmas
last night,'' Jack Wittman, the father of Master Sgt. David Lee
O'Connor, said Sunday. ``I am 62 years old and will never live to
have a better Christmas than the one last night.''
   However, he said, ``I feel so sorry for the other people. My
heart goes out to them because I know what they are feeling.''
   Wittman said he talked to his son Christmas Eve, two days after
being told by Pan Am that the soldier, stationed in West Germany,
had been on the plane that crashed and killed all 258 aboard.
   ``He didn't know nothing about it,'' Wittman said. ``He was kind
of upset and didn't know what was going on. He said, `I am alive and
doing well.' When we both quit crying and settled down I told him I
loved him and wished he was here. Thank God he wasn't on the plane.''
   The false information apparently came from a listing of ``D.
O'Connor,'' Wittman said. But the actual victim was Daniel E.
O'Connor, 31, of Boston, who was a security agent for the State
Department in Nicosia, Cyprus.
   Wittman, who is retired from a Sapulpa glass company, said the
mistaken notification of his son's death sent shock waves through
his family as it gathered to celebrate Christmas. His son had sent
him a letter last month indicating that he would try to return to
Oklahoma for the Christmas holidays.
   ``Hell's not the word,'' Wittman said. ``Nobody knows what it's
like until they go through it. If it hadn't been for prayer and the
church I belong to here I couldn't have made it.''
</TEXT>
