<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Non-PregnancyPay     12-26 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Non-Pregnancy Pay,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Program Pays Teens $1 A Day Not To Get Pregnant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial Denver program that pays teen-age
girls $1 a day not to get pregnant is proving one of the most
successful methods of curbing the teen pregnancy rate, supporters
say.
   The program was introduced at La Mariposa Health Station three
years ago, and prompted criticism even from many supporters of
family planning, who saw it as paternal and coercive.
   Supporters of the program don't claim to have found the ultimate
solution to the teen-age pregnancy problem, but they say on a small
scale it works and costs less in the long run.
   Between 30 percent and 50 percent of teen-agers who become
pregnant once are likely to become pregnant again before they're 18.
But of 18 original participants in the Denver program, only 17
percent had a repeat pregnancy.
   Gov. Roy Romer's Initiative on Teen Pregnancy reported that
Colorado spends more than $200 million annually in Aid to Families
with Dependent Children, food stamps, Medicaid and other public
assistance for families headed by women who began their childbearing
as teens.
   To earn their money, all the teen-agers have to do is show up
once a week at the west side clinic for a group session. La Mariposa
counselor Diane Medina presides over a stack of dollar bills and a
smorgasbord of snacks. She just listens to the conversation and
makes no demands.
   About a dozen teen-agers are regulars; others come occasionally
or drop by to pick up their $7 and leave.
   ``There are no hard and fast rules,'' said medical director Dr.
Peggy LaTourrette. ``They can talk about anything they want to. This
is the only group, the one place ... they can come in and nobody's
telling them what to do, nobody's giving them rules and
regulations.''
   Officials at Rocky Mountain Planned Parenthood have had their
hands slapped by their national headquarters for funding the
program, but they hope to prop it up for another year. The program
lacks funding for 1989.
   Supporters say anyone with $1 a day to contribute to the project
can ``sponsor'' a teen-ager, significantly decreasing the odds that
she will give birth to a child before she's 18.
   Desiree Ramos, 16, has earned $462 through the program which, for
her, is spending money. She had an abortion at 13, and still wants
children ``but I want to wait until I'm 20, maybe 21.''
   ``I want to have enough to buy him what he wants. I don't want
him stealing. I don't want us living in the projects,'' she said.
</TEXT>
