<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WineVandal     12-26 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wine Vandal,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vandal Uncorks Winery's Vats, Spilling 450,000 Gallons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CERES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three huge storage vats were uncorked at a
winery, creating a 450,000-gallon pink sea, and authorities said the
motive may involve sour grapes.
   Valves to the storage vats were opened before sunrise Saturday at
Bronco Wine Co., located on the outskirts of Modesto, said
Stanislaus County sheriff's investigators.
   Over five hours, 344,000 gallons of white wine and another
106,000 gallons of red wine flowed from the vats at a loss of
$800,000, said Detective Jane Irwin.
   The culprit may be a disgruntled former or current employee,
because the complex valves on the vats would be difficult for an
outsider to open, she said. Winery employees were being interviewed.
   Bronco Wine executive John Franzia said he was upset about the
loss, but he spent little time crying over spilled wine.
   ``There's nothing I can do about it,'' he said. ``It's done.''
   A winery security guard discovered the spill at 9:30 a.m. Five
hours earlier, everything had been dry, Franzia said.
   Workers pumped the wine into an adjacent field and road,
surprising deputies, who drove into a 3-foot-deep pool of the
liquid. Wine rose to the patrol car doors, Ms. Irwin said.
   She said she initially thought the liquid was water dumped by
recent storms, but then noticed that the pool had a bouquet and
blush.
</TEXT>
