<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Tornadoes     12-26 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tornadoes,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tornado Survivors Begin Searching Through Rubble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and relatives of a man killed by a
twister that swirled through two Nashville suburbs, destroying 20
buildings, used power saws in an attempt to salvage their buried
belongings.
   ``We've picked around a little bit, trying to get things on the
edges,'' said Victor McMillan, son-in-law of Ernest Rice, 67, who
was killed by one of eight tornadoes in the region on Saturday.
   ``It'll be bulldozed and carted off,'' McMillan said. ``We're
trying to get into areas we haven't been able to reach.''
   Police officers and state troopers sent in by Gov. Ned McWherter
patrolled the area to deter looting, but officials said curiosity
seekers tying up traffic have been the worst problem.
   ``The biggest problem has been sightseers,'' said Mike Thompson,
emergency management director for Williamson County.
   The twister cut a three-mile path that also damaged 45 homes and
17 businesses, officials said. Thompson estimated the damage to
houses at $3 million.
   Fifteen people injured by the tornado were examined at Williamson
Medical Center, but only one was admitted. Lucy McClearon of College
Grove was listed in stable condition today.
   Several hotels gave free lodging to tornado victims.
   McMillan recalled that as the tornado hit, he and his wife were
lifted into the air and shot outside the house.
   ``We were very quickly outside in the dark and the rain,'' he
said. ``We ended up out in the gravel.''
   Many of those whose homes or businesses were destroyed were
distraught, while others were stoic.
   ``We're having a great Christmas,'' said Mary Ann Power as family
members salvaged material from her office supply business, Power
Enterprises.
   ``What can you do. It's happened. It's just a fact of life.
They're just material things. We can replace that.''
</TEXT>
