<HEAD>Governor Remains in Hospital, Jokes With Doctors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Mickelson, injured in a
snowmobile accident over the weekend, was in good condition today
and even felt good enough to joke with hospital personnel, an aide
said.
   ``He said he didn't want to get on the hopsital scale because it
weighs heavier than the one at home,'' said Gretchen Lord Anderson,
Mickelson's press aide.
   The governor was in the special care unit at St. Mary's Hospital
in Pierre, and Anderson said he might be moved into a regular room
today. Mickelson probably will remain hospitalized at least through
Saturday.
   Mickelson, 47, suffered a broken collarbone and four broken ribs
when his snowmobile dropped about 10 feet into a ravine and he was
thrown off during an outing with his family Saturday afternoon.
   Mickelson slept well Sunday night, Anderson said.
   ``He put in a good night's rest, but he's still in a lot of
pain,'' she said.
