<DOCNO> AP881226-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MulroyProfile     12-26 1055</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mulroy Profile,1086</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`If You Need Anything at All. ...'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto NY10</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Mulroy, described by a colleague as a
balding leprechaun six feet tall, was a man who made things work.
   An emergency electrical system for The Associated Press in Lima,
to use when guerrilla actions led to blackouts.
   A satellite setup that carried AP accounts of the Olympic games
in Seoul to a receiver in London, and on to the world's newspapers
and broadcasters.
   A balky communications link in Hong Kong _ with repairs
prescribed long distance while he was in a hotel room in Istanbul.
   ``Morning, how's everything?'' he said before he talked the Hong
Kong correspondent through the problem, apologizing that the
telephone conversation would have to share his attention with a
hasty shave so that he could get to the airport.
   Many days, John Mulroy lived on airplanes.
   Last Wednesday he died on one.
   Mulroy, 59, director of international communications for the AP,
was one of 258 people killed aboard Pan Am Flight 103 when it
crashed into a village in southern Scotland, across the Irish Sea
from his native Ireland.
   His son Sean, 25, his daughter-in-law Ingrid, and three other
members of his family died with him.
   Airplane stories were part of the Mulroy lore. He was the
unflappable flier. He'd take his seat, make the sign of the cross,
and take a nap while the plane climbed to altitude.
   He caught the last plane out of Ankara in a March blizzard this
year, cheerful and joking through a flight that clipped a snowbank
on takeoff and bounced through gale force winds afterward.
   Heading from Tokyo to Moscow he looked down at Siberia. ``If we
have to go down here it will take them a long time to find us,'' he
told a colleague. ``And it's cold, too.''
   Mulroy, a 25-year veteran of Pan Am before he joined the AP 4 1@2
years ago, enjoyed flying.
   ``If you're in a vibrant, moving industry, it's always
pleasant,'' he said in an interview conducted for the AP employee
magazine on Nov. 30. ``Because you get off the plane and you know
there's something to be done and you've got to move forward. . .''
   For all the millions of miles he covered, Mulroy said he knew
nothing about jet lag. ``I can get on an airplane to sleep or to
work, one of the two. And I get off the airplane ready to go to work
again.''
   He spoke in what Lou Boccardi, president of the AP, called an
authoritative whisper. It was unmistakably Irish, a heritage that
was his pride. He was a naturalized U.S. citizen.
   Mulroy and his wife, Joan, sent their three children _ Sean,
Siobhan, 26, and Brendan, 23 _ back to Ireland to attend high
school. The family vacationed there each summer, in a house at
Cloongee, near Mulroy's birthplace.
   He'd built it for his father, a widower who raised six children
by himself. When his father died, it became Mulroy's Irish base.
He'd had it renovated and enlarged, and was planning to spend more
time there after he retired, although there were those who wagered
he wouldn't have retired anyhow.
   Mulroy's Roman Catholic faith was deeply held; he counted an
audience and brief conversation with Pope John Paul II one of the
high points of his life.
   In Seoul for the Olympics, he slipped away to attend Mass at a
Korean Church. ``I didn't understand a word of it, but it was
grand,'' he said.
   At the end of another Korean Mass, the priest switched to
English, greeted Mulroy and a colleague and asked them to stand.
Mulroy was up in an instant, nodding and smiling as 800 Korean
churchgoers applauded. He took the arm of his shy colleague and
pulled him up, too.
   A memorial Mass was being said Monday night at St. Francis of
Assisi Church in Greenlawn, on Long Island.
   After his quarter-century career at Pan Am, where he began as a
Long Island City ticket agent and became director of communications,
Mulroy joined the AP in August 1984.
   It quickly became part of his identity _ and vice versa. He was
known worldwide as the AP man. In Moscow, he joined all the toasts
but scrimped on the vodka. At the Great Wall of China, he
encountered a group of quigong masters, men studied in the Chinese
way of harnessing vital powers. He watched as four of them lifted
their teacher using only their thumbs. Then they lifted Mulroy,
although not very far.
   When bureaucrats and import restrictions got in the way of making
things work, he knew how to talk, cajole or smuggle his way around
them.
   His handshake was as firm _ crushing to some _ as his brogue was
hoarse and whispery. That low voice took on a different significance
to his colleagues only after his death, when they learned that he
had suffered from cancer and had a lung removed about six years ago,
before he joined the AP. He told no one; he didn't want it thought
that he was less than fit, or that he should ease his pace.
   He never did. Because his assignment was worldwide, time zones
meant nothing. The telephone rang at his home in East Northport, on
Long Island, at all hours. And Mulroy would answer, at 3 a.m., with
a sweetly Irish ``Good Morning.''
   One call came while he was in Ireland, fishing near his house.
His wife, Joan, called him in. Mulroy dealt with the problem. ``You
made me miss catching my dinner _ you owe me one,'' he said.
   He had that right. The AP and its people owed him more than one.
And the feeling was mutual. Mulroy was proud of his company and his
colleagues. Some he designated honorary Irishmen, among them Masaaki
Iwasa of Tokyo, and Francois Ghattas of Beirut and Nicosia.
   ``A small group, but the greatest bunch of talent I've ever
seen,'' Mulroy said of his AP associates in the Nov. 30 interview.
``Hours and time never seem to matter.''
   Mulroy set the standard. As he left an AP town, the words that
came just before goodbye were a litany:
   ``If you need anything at all, just let me know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0062 </DOCNO>
