<HEAD>Five Hindu Bus Passengers Killed by Sikh Militants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday found the bodies of five
bus passengers shot and killed by suspected Sikh militants in Punjab.
   The assailants on Sunday stopped a state-owned bus, ordered all
seven Hindu passengers to get off, and took them into the jungle.
   After a 30-hour search, police discovered the bodies of five
Hindus along with two seriously wounded passengers in the Mand area
of Punjab, said the area's police chief, Anil Kaushik.
   In another incident Monday, suspected Sikh militants shot and
killed five other people in Punjab, including a family of three.
   The militants have been blamed for more than 2,400 killings this
year in the northern state.
   Militant Sikhs have been fighting for an independent homeland in
Punjab since 1982, claiming discrimination by the Hindu community.
Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 880 million people, but are a
majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
