<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Press     12-26 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Press,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Handful of Western Publications to Be Sold Officially</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special kiosks in major cities will begin selling a
few hundred copies of Western newspapers and magazines beginning
Jan. 1, the Tass news agency said Monday.
   ``The fact that the new arrivals, which certainly cannot be
called `pro-Soviet,' will be sold here at all says a lot about
increased openness in the Soviet Union,'' the official news agency
said.
   But the small number of papers to be made available and the
average reader's lack of knowledge of English ensure that few people
will have access to the publications.
   Tass said among the publications to be sold from the special
kiosks will be The Guardian, The Times, and the Financial Times from
Britain, the International Herald Tribune, and the magazines Time
and Newsweek.
   Tass initially said 350 copies of The Guardian, and 400 copies of
the Financial Times and International Herald Tribune will be sold
daily. It did not say where besides Moscow they will be sold.
   The number of papers offered for sale are likely to increase, the
report said.
   Distribution of such publications have long been prohibited in
the Soviet Union on ideological grounds. But since the Moscow summit
between President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Reagan, a
limited number have been available at the Soviet Foreign Ministry's
press center.
   Access to the press center generally is limited to accredited
correspondents, so few people had the opportunity to buy the papers
there.
</TEXT>
