<DOCNO> AP881226-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1151EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Poll Bjt   12-26 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Poll, Bjt,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Ratings: Popular Personally, Less So on Policies</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY39</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans believe President Reagan has helped the
rich and hurt the poor, but a wide majority nonetheless approve of
his work in the White House, according to a national poll.
   Majorities in the Media General-Associated Press survey gave
negative grades to Reagan's social policies and ethics enforcement,
rated his judgment unfavorably and said they would not have
supported him for a third term.
   At the same time, an overwhelming two-thirds approved of the way
Reagan has done his job overall and said history will view him
positively, and 55 percent said he has bettered the nation.
   The telephone survey was conducted among a random sample of 1,084
adults shortly after last month's election. Reagan leaves office
Jan. 20.
   The poll found two factors at the heart of Reagan's popularity:
Wide belief that his economic policies have helped the nation and
high regard for his leadership. He also scored well on defense and
U.S.-Soviet relations.
   Reagan's ratings flagged elsewhere. While nearly two-thirds said
his economic policies have been good for the nation, for example, a
mighty 80 percent rated his handling of the budget deficit
negatively.
   Moreover, 54 percent said the poor are worse off economically as
a result of Reagan's policies, and 72 percent said wealthy Americans
are better off. Opinion was more divided on the middle class:
one-third called it worse off, a quarter said better off and the
rest saw little change.
   A third of respondents said they and their families were better
off as a result of Reagan's efforts, and 18 percent said worse off.
But they split evenly when asked to score Reagan's handling of the
economy, and more than twice as many picked the worst rating as
chose the best. The poll gave ``excellent'' or ``good'' as positive
choices, ``only fair'' or ``poor'' as negatives.
   Reagan received negative ratings for his handling of every social
issue posed: civil rights, 51 percent negative; education, 54
percent negative; housing, 65 percent negative, and welfare, 67
percent negative. Six in 10 rated him negatively on his handling of
ethics in government.
   In all these gauges Reagan fared worst among Democrats but also
was rated negatively by most independents. Majorities of Republicans
endorsed him on most issues but not on the deficit, welfare or
housing.
   On two other issues, he scored extraordinarily well: Seven in 10
rated him favorably for defense policies and eight in 10 rated him
positively on handling relations with the Soviets.
   Six in 10 viewed Reagan's other foreign policies favorably. The
poll was done before he opened contact with the Palestine Liberation
Organization this month.
   Even with his mixed policy ratings, six in 10 respondents ranked
Reagan positively for his accomplishments in office overall and
two-thirds rated his leadership ability as excellent or good. A full
three-quarters favorably rated his charisma and ability to
communicate.
   On his judgment as president, 53 percent rated him negatively.
But he was seen as effective: Six in 10 said he has accomplished
most of what he set out to do.
   On his effectiveness, as in many other issues, Reagan did best
with the youngest adults, age 18-29, and worst with the oldest, 65
and over. He also did considerably better with men than with women.
   Fifty-two percent said they would not have voted Reagan for a
third term if he were legally allowed to seek one _ down from 64
percent when the Media General-AP poll asked the question last
spring. Half the men polled, but just 37 percent of the women,
favored a third Reagan term.
   The survey, conducted Nov. 10-20, has a margin of error of plus
or minus three percentage points.
   Media General Inc., a communications company based in Richmond,
Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News
Leader, the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in Charleston,
S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1153EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Violence     12-26 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Violence,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Peace Appeals, Black Factions Continue Fighting in Natal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was no Christmas lull in
the fighting between black factions in Natal Province, despite a
peace appeal from Archbishop Desmond Tutu, and police said nine more
blacks have died in the country's worst conflict.
   Most died from stab wounds in six separate incidents Sunday in
the troubled province. A dozen homes were set afire, 17 people were
injured, and police used tear gas to break up two street battles.
   More than 1,000 blacks have been killed in Natal in the past two
years in the feuding between supporters of militant anti-apartheid
groups and members of Inkatha, a more moderate movement led by Zulu
politician Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
   Tutu, the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize laureate who heads southern
Africa's Anglican Church, last week deplored the violence in this
southeastern province.
   ``When we are meant to be celebrating the birth of the Prince of
Peace, the killing looks as though it is escalating,'' the black
archbishop said. ``In such a situation it is easy to be dispairing.
Calling for peace can seem a meaningless ritual.''
   Black leaders had expressed optimism in September, when officials
of Inkatha and the Congress of South African Trade Unions signed a
peace pact in the Natal provincial capital, Pietermaritzburg. The
militant labor federation is allied with the banned United
Democratic Front _ an umbrella organization for anti-apartheid
groups _ in the power struggle against Inkatha.
   The agreement condemned violence and established a board to
review residents' complaints of harassment or attacks.
   The pact remains in effect, but has had limited success. Some
witnesses have been afraid to testify and many supporters of the
United Democratic Front, which is banned from holding meetings, felt
they were not consulted about the agreement.
   This month, increasing violence has further dimmed the hopes
raised by the peace pact. On Dec. 3, gunmen fired into a house in
Trust Feed, a black community near Pietermaritzburg, and killed 11
people, including children, who were holding an all-night vigil for
a child who had died.
   News reports initially blamed Inkatha for the massacre. Buthelezi
later claimed the victims were Inkatha members and threatened to sue
anyone who blamed his organization.
   On Dec. 17, residents of Caluza, also near Pietermaritzburg, said
Inkatha members rampaged through town, killing three people and
damaging dozens of homes while police stood by.
   Police officials deny any partiality in the conflict.
   Tutu, in his peace appeal, raised the issue of police bias.
   ``I am very disturbed to hear reports that people do not perceive
the police as a force which protects them, but rather as a group
which favors those who claim allegiance to the Inkatha movement,''
he said.
   The country's largest-selling black daily newspaper, The Sowetan,
said in a recent editorial the ``reign of terror'' in Natal was ``a
shame and a disgrace.''
   Both Inkatha, which claims 1.5 million members, and the United
Democratic Front oppose the apartheid policies under which South
Africa's 5 million whites dominate the 26 million blacks, who have
not voice in national affairs. But the strategies of the two groups
differ markedly.
   The front, a predominantly black coalition of about 600 groups,
advocates economic sanctions, strikes and other confrontational
tactics to bring about sweeping political and economic change.
   Inkatha, which opposes sanctions and shuns militant protest,
accuses the front of supporting the violence of the outlawed African
National Congress, the largest guerrilla group fighting the
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Belgium-Soviet     12-26 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Belgium-Soviet,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Cooperation With West Produces First Flowers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Europe-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet economic openness toward the West
is only budding, but it already has produced some flowers, even
though they're plastic.
   The first parcel of plastic flowers and kitchenware from the
southern Soviet city of Tashkent reached this port city a couple of
weeks ago, palpable proof that joint ventures with Soviet companies
are not necessarily mired in delays and red tape.
   ``There are already dividends after only one year,'' said Frans
Moens of the Antwerp Plastic Merchandising Co.
   Moens, holding a bouquet of red plastic roses, said Antwerp
Plastic controls one of Europe's oldest producers of plastic flowers
_ Italy's Alma Rose SpA _ which was approached last year by the
Soviets.
   Alma Rose had long wanted to be a trailblazer with the Soviets.
Since the early 1970s, it offered its services ``but always met a
`nyet' (Leonid) Brezhnev-style,'' said Moens, referring to the
former Soviet leader.
   But things moved quickly with the emergence of Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and his program for economic reform.
   Talks started in March 1987, and six months later the $40 million
joint venture Sovplastital was founded. A Soviet state company holds
78 percent of the shares, with the remainder held by Alma Rose. On
the board of directors, however, parity reigns.
   Key to doing successful business with the Soviets, said Moens,
was setting up an all-encompassing business plan. ``The Soviets
rigorously stick to the plan but absolutely everything has to be in
it,'' he said. He compared this with the more practical approach of
European businesses.
   For Tashkent, the Soviets wanted machines, materials and the
know-how to refine the plastic products while gaining an export
market to earn them foreign currency.
   Antwerp Plastic and Alma Rose gained a new production unit _
where wages are still low _ and a market of 280 million potential
customers. ``The market is simply enormous and still has to be
claimed,'' said Moens.
   An Antwerp Plastic official, who demanded anonymity, also said
Alma Rose wanted to reduce production in Italy ``because of the many
(labor) strikes. That is not the case in the Soviet Union.''
   The factory in Tashkent employs 800 workers and plans to add 300
soon, Moens said.
   The plastic wares, including flowers, hot-colored pots in the
shape of pears and apples and plates of intertwined fake leaves, are
mainly sold domestically through state shops. But the joint venture
already has set up Western-style shops in Tashkent and Moscow.
   Moens said the mayor of Leningrad also made inquiries about a
shop.
   As the first Belgian company involved in a Soviet joint venture,
Antwerp Plastic often is asked for information. About six companies,
mostly in the chemical sector, are negotiating, but no deals have
come through.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet     12-26 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Ideology Chief Criticizes Press, Informal Organizations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin ideology chief in a speech published
Monday attacked some state-run publications for sensationalism and a
lack of regard for facts under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policy of greater openness.
   Vadim A. Medvedev, who was named to the ruling Communist Party
Politburo by Gorbachev in September and immediately given control
over ideology and propaganda, also indicated there would be no
lessening of control over the mass media.
   ``People are concerned about hysteria, sensationalism, the
destructive direction of some statements, the inciting of passions,
lack of regard for the facts, a deficit of professionalism,'' and
other tendencies in the Soviet press, Medvedev said in a speech to
local party officials in Kazan.
   ``The mass media must obey general laws, develop in the framework
of the laws of socialist government,'' he said. A new law on the
press is being written, but ``no law can take away the civic
position, the party responsibility of the leaders of the mass media,
of our entire journalistic body.''
   His comments at the Dec. 23-24 conference were published Monday
by the Communist Party newspaper Pravda.
   State-controlled press and publishers have used the new
atmosphere of greater freedom under Gorbachev to publish material
that were not acceptable or were banned for years under Gorbachev's
predecessors.
   But since taking control over the party's ideology and propaganda
apparatus, Medvedev also has signaled that ``glasnost,'' the policy
of greater openness, has definite limits.
   On Nov. 29, Medvedev told a news conference that he opposed
publication of works by exiled writer Alexander Solzhenitsyn because
they would undermine Soviet society. Some writers, artists and
activists in informal political groups have been clamoring for
publication of works by the Nobel-prize winning author who was
stripped of his citizenship and exiled in 1974.
   Medvedev's speech was one of a series published by Pravda on
Monday by top party leaders at regional conferences reviewing local
party membership in accord with a directive from the June Communist
Party conference to cleanse party rolls of people who were standing
in the way of Gorbachev's reform policies.
   Medvedev also criticized party and government traditionalists,
who he said were standing in the way of Gorbachev' reforms. He said
the party was trying to steer a course between extremists who wanted
no reform and those who wanted too much, too fast.
   His statement contrasted with a speech in the Ural Mountains city
of Perm two weeks ago by Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, who
emphasized the need for more democracy and openness.
   ``Democracy, glasnost and differences of opinion still frighten
us, as if every one of us constantly lives in agreement with himself
and always thinks in comfortable cliches,'' said Yakovlev,
considered the Politburo member closest to Gorbachev. ``Can you
really call a person a person if he doesn't have his own opinions?''
Yakovlev asked.
   Pravda said Medvedev's comments on the Soviet media referred to a
few publications it did not identify. But they most likely referred
to the handful of journals and newspapers that have been pushing the
frontiers of Gorbachev's glasnost policy to publish revelations
about Soviet history and social problems that previously never would
have surfaced in the official press.
   Leading those publications are the weeklies Ogonyok and Moscow
News. More conservative publications continue to publish less
controversial material, except for several instances in which open
disputes have broken out in the pages of the official media between
progressive and traditional papers.
   The accusation that some publications were inciting passions also
was likely aimed at local newspapers in the Baltic republics and in
the southern republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   In both places the official media accused local media of adding
to ethnic rather than quieting it.
   Medvedev also served notice on informal political organizations
that have sprung up outside the Communist Party that they will be
tolerated only as long as they do not run counter to party policy.
   Medvedev said the informal groups are a ``natural part of the
process of restructuring.'' Some people, he said, are using a
``healthy process for establishing and movement of anti-socialist
goals.''
   ``Our main criterion for determining relations with autonomous
organizations is their correspondence with the goals of
restructuring, ideological renewal, socialist choice,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
