<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan     12-26 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Assembly to Consider Limiting President's Tenure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly, Taiwan's electoral
college, said Monday it will consider a request from President Lee
Teng-hui that would limit the number of terms a president can hold.
   Lee, 65, proposed the change Sunday when the National Assembly
convened a special three-day session to commemorate the anniversary
of the adoption of the Nationalist constitution on Dec. 25, 1947.
   Under the constitution, a president is limited to two consecutive
six-year terms. The clause was revised by an emergency decree in
1960 that allowed Nationalist leader Chiang Kai-shek to serve as
president until his death in 1975. Chiang was president for 27 years.
   He was later succeeded by his son, Chiang Ching-kuo, who served
10 years before he died earlier this year. The younger Chiang was
succeeded by Lee, who is serving out the remainder of Chiang's term,
which expires in May 1990.
   The Nationalists retreated to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil
war to the communists in mainland China. Both the Nationalists and
communist Chinese maintain they are the legitimate government of
both Taiwan and China.
   The emergency decree extending the presidential term was passed
at a time of heightened tension between the rival Chinese
governments.
   Before his death, Chiang Ching-kuo initiated democratic reforms
that included a more lenient Nationalist policy toward the
communists. Lee has vowed to continue the policy.
   He told the National Assembly a limited presidential term would
make the government ``more responsive to the public's demand for
democracy.''
   Members of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party, who
disrupted Sunday's session, wants the emergency decree abolished
because they say it gives the president too much power.
   Lee, the first native Taiwanese to head the Nationalist
government, gave no indication what limit to the presidential term
he supports, but observers say he is likely to back the two-term
presidency.
   Of the 894 members of the National Assembly, 768 belong to the
governing Nationalist Party. Lee, who is chairman of the party, is
expected to be a candidate for election to his first full term as
president in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
