<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Moslems     12-26 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Moslems,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>57 Extremists Arrested, Another 50 Sought in Assiut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces arrested 57 Moslem
fundamentalist students suspected of anti-state activities and are
searching for another 50, police sources said Monday.
   Detainees were seized as they distributed leaflets attacking
President Hosni Mubarak and Interior Minister Zaki Badr, who handles
internal security, according to the sources, who spoke on condition
of anonymity. The leaflets demanded the release of other detained
students.
   About 300 people thought to be Moslem extremists have been
rounded up this month in this city 230 miles south of Cairo, the
sources said. Most were students from Assiut University.
   It coincided with an anti-extremist crackdown in Cairo and other
cities in which about 500 people have been arrested.
   The operation is being carried out under an emergency law enacted
immediately after Moslem extremists assassinated President Anwar
Sadat in Cairo on Oct. 6, 1981.
   Informants said security forces were searching for another 50
Assiut University students who fled the city.
   For almost a decade, Assiut has been a center of agitation by
Moslem fundamentalists demanding immediate implementation, by
violence if necessary, of the stringent Islamic legal and social
code known as Sharia.
   Assiut University, which has about 50,000 students, has seen
frequent clashes between fundamentalist students and police and
between rival moderate and extremist factions of the Moslem zealots.
About 100 students were injured in one inter-student clash at the
beginning of this month.
   Badr said last week there are about 825 extremist students at the
university.
   The minister also said extremists had desecrated 25 of the
nation's 70,000 mosques by using them to store arms and trade in
drugs to finance their activities.
</TEXT>
