<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Unions     12-26 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Unions,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister, Unions Agree To Discuss Differences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez and
leaders of Spain's two biggest trade unions agreed Monday to new
talks to resolve differences that led to a paralyzing nationwide
strike.
   Gonzalez announced he agreed to form a ``socio-economic council''
with the unions to study five demands they made after the Dec. 15
general work stoppage.
   ``I hope this will continue to be a habit, a future custom above
all, if we are able to institutionalize a forum for dialogue,''
Gonzalez told a news conference after meeting leaders of the
Socialist General Workers Unions and the Communist Workers
Commissions.
   Antonio Gutierrez, secretary-general of the communist union, said
the meeting was worthwhile, but ``more progress could have been
made.''
   Union demands include increased wages for civil servants and
pensioners hurt by an unexpected rise in inflation, unemployment
insurance for more workers, and collective bargaining provisions for
civil servants.
   Gonzalez already has agreed to a demand he withdraw a government
plan to spur youth employment, which included reducing minimum wages
for those under 25.
   In a Dec. 21 address to parliament, he also said bowing to the
unions' demand to extend government unemployment insurance to cover
48 percent of Spain's 2.7 million jobless was ``impossible'' because
``neither the budget nor the economy could stand it.''
   Gonzalez told legislators that Spanish civil servants had union
rights equal to those in other European countries, making the
collective bargaining demand unnecessary.
   He urged the unions to negotiate with the government to ensure
the country maintains its 5 percent annual growth rate.
   Monday's four-hour meeting was the first encounter between
representatives of government and organized labor since the Dec. 14
strike in which 7.8 million of 11.8 million employed Spaniards
stayed home to call for a bigger share of benefits from the booming
economy.
   The two labor leaders boycotted a Dec. 22 meeting called by
Gonzalez because they objected to the presence of the head of the
country's main employers' association.
   After Monday's meeting, the socialist union's Secretary-General
Nicolas Redondo said he expected most negotiations to be limited to
government and union representatives.
   ``For certain concrete issues the business leaders could attend.
But not when we are trying to formulate a progressive employment
policy,'' he said.
   Labor leaders accuse the Socialist government of siding with a
thriving business community while abandoning workers still suffering
wage restrictions and other concessions the unions made to help
transform Spain's once-sluggish economy.
   Since the Socialists first won a parliamentary majority in 1982,
annual inflation has been cut from more than 14 percent to just over
5 percent. But unemployment remains the highest in Europe at 18.7
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
