<HEAD>Albania Attacks Serbian Nationalism in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper in Albania
has made an unusually strong attack on Serbian nationalism in a
province of Yugoslavia dominated by ethnic Albanians, an official
report said.
   In an article Sunday, the daily Zeri i Popullit said Yugoslavia
always has been split by the desire of the southern Slavs to unite
under Serbian domination, according to the ATA Albanian news agency,
monitored in Vienna.
   Serb nationalists have staged mass demonstrations this year
demanding more control over their medieval heartland of Kosovo, a
province bordering Albania and dominated by ethnic Albanians.
   Serbs, the largest of more than 20 ethnic groups in Yugoslavia,
charge that Albanians in Kosovo _ who have staged anti-Serbian
protests _ want to secede from the Yugoslav federation and unite
with Albania.
   But Zeri i Popullit said the ethnic Albanians' revolt stems from
a desire to be treated as equals in Yugoslavia. The Albanians say
they are being harassed by the Serbs, and demand that their
Serbian-controlled province be made a separate republic.
   Yugoslavia is a federation of six republics and two autonomous
provinces constituted after the communists took power following
World War II.
</TEXT>
