<HEAD>Mobs Riot After Slaying of Lawmaker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with 20 dead. Picks up 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants with axes killed a state
legislator and two other people in a southern city Monday, and at
least 20 died when mobs angered by the deaths rampaged and set fire
to buildings, news reports said.
   Thirteen people died and more than 100 were injured in the riots
in Vijayawada, about 850 miles southeast of New Delhi. Police opened
fire into the crowds, killing at least four other people, the
reports said.
   The army and paramilitary troops were deployed in Vijayawada to
help police restore order. Authorities imposed a 24-hour curfew on
the city of 500,000 people, and police were ordered to shoot at
rioters, the reports said.
   Rioting began after the slaying of Mohan Ranga Rao, a state
legislator of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress Party.
   Ranga Rao, 48, went on a hunger strike Thursday, saying he was
protesting police oppression, said Press Trust of India without
elaborating. News reports said Ranga Rao and some of his supporters
had set up a camp in the city.
   Vijayawada is in Andhra Pradesh state, which is governed by the
opposition Telegu Desam Party.
   Assailants armed with axes threw smoke bombs and then attacked
and killed the lawmaker and two of his supporters, according to
Press Trust of India.
   Other supporters attacked the assailants as they fled, and two
people were killed, the news agency said. It did not identify the
victims.
   Angry Congress Party supporters responded by setting fire to
buses, movie houses, hotels, shops and a newspaper office in
Vijaywada, United News of India said. It said rioting also was
reported in the towns of Tenali, Tadapalligudam, Eluru,
Visakhapatnam and Hyderabad, the state capital.
   Congress supporters set fire to three buses in Hydebarad and
attacked homes owned by relatives of Chief Minister N.T. Rama Rao,
the news agency said.
</TEXT>
