<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY44, TOK1, TOK4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson whirled and twirled his way Monday
through a show billed in the Japanese press as a ``farewell
concert'' but made no mention of retiring.
   Jackson spoke to the audience only briefly during the two-hour
show, the ninth and final concert of his current stand in Tokyo,
saying: ``Domo arigato (thank you) to everyone in Japan'' and ``I
love you, Japan.''
   In August, Jackson's manager, Frank Dileo, said the tour probably
would be Jackson's last. He said Jackson, 30, would go on to ``do
movies and other things.''
   Tokyo was supposed to be the final stop on the 14-month,
four-continent tour. But three shows in Los Angeles that were
canceled last month because Jackson had throat problems have been
rescheduled for next month.
   After Dileo's comments, newspapers dubbed the Tokyo appearances
Jackson's ``farewell concerts'' and promoters sold T-shirts and hats
emblazoned with that slogan.
   The nine concerts _ 450,000 tickets in all in the 50,000-seat
Tokyo Dome _ were quick sellouts.
   ``It's going to be lonely without Michael. It's as though his
life is over,'' said Yuriko Wada, an office worker from Kyoto who
attended the concert.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While she says she's deeply in love, newlywed
actress Amanda Pays admits there are things she'd like to change
about husband Corbin Bernsen.
   In the January issue of Self magazine, Ms. Pays of ``Max
Headroom'' said Bernsen _ the lothario divorce lawyer Arnold Becker
on ``L.A. Law'' _ is too fat around the middle, owns too many cowboy
boots and is too hot-tempered.
   ``It's not healthy throwing a deck chair in front of 10 people,''
she said.
   Bernsen said he'd like their child, due in March, to have his
wife's ``style and class, plus the thing that I have, that American
dream to kind of go for it.''
   He said family life is a top priority, but he remains committed
to his work.
   ``Next to Amanda, my greatest passion is my work, but what I do
get jealous about is her ability to do more quality things because
of her classical nature,'' he said. ``People are willing to pay me
to do a physical comedy, but I want to be able to do a passionate
`Hope and Glory' kind of movie.''
