<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Carpenter says he still doesn't
understand the 1983 death of his sister and singing partner, Karen
Carpenter, but he feels the life of an entertainer had nothing to do
with it.
   Miss Carpenter died of complications brought on by anorexia
nervosa, an eating disorder characterized by extreme dieting. Her
life and death are the subject of the TV movie ``The Karen Carpenter
Story'' on CBS next week.
   ``If she had died in a more tangible way, if she had been hit by
a car, it would have been equally tragic, but something I could
comprehend,'' Carpenter writes in the Dec. 31 issue of TV Guide.
``The eating disorder that killed her, anorexia nervosa, was little
understood then and only a little more now.''
   Carpenter is executive producer of the movie.
   ``What would possess a woman like her to starve herself?''
Carpenter asks. ``Some people blame it on career pressure or a need
to take more control over her life.
   ``I don't think so. I think she would have suffered from the same
problem even if she had been a homemaker.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen Silverman's book about Daryl F.
Zanuck's vicious power struggle with his son Richard for control of
20th Century Fox didn't exactly put him on Richard Zanuck's
Christmas list.
   ``I wasn't out to write a puff piece on the guy, but I don't
really think he'll stay mad for very long,'' Silverman, 37, said
recently about his book, ``The Fox That Got Away.''
   ``Besides, we aren't exactly running in the same social circles,
anyway. I doubt if I lost any party invitations because of the
book.''
   Richard Zanuck ousted his father, one of Hollywood's last
old-style movie moguls, to win control of 20th Century. But a final
move by the elder Zanuck ruined his son's studio career.
   ``It's about fathers and sons, period, and that alone is of
interest to people,'' Silverman said of the book, his first.
   Zanuck died in 1979. His son became a successful independent
producer with David Brown, working on such films as ``Jaws,'' ``The
Sting'' and ``Cocoon.''
