<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1408EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Poll     12-26 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Poll,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gallup Poll Will Test Soviets' Knowledge of Geography, Survey
Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, which for decades banned accurate
maps as a security risk and outlawed public opinion surveys as
anti-communist, will allow the Gallup poll to survey its citizens'
knowledge of geography, it was reported Monday.
   The poll of 1,500 to 2,000 people apparently is aimed at
discovering whether Soviet citizens are as ignorant as Americans of
such basic facts as the location of Great Britain.
   A recent international poll by Gallup and the National Geographic
Society found that three out of four Americans couldn't find the
Persian Gulf on a map and most couldn't find Britain. Americans
ranked sixth among the eight nations tested.
   Adult Americans averaged 8.6 correct answers out of 16, far
behind the Swedes at 11.6. The West Germans scored with 11.2, the
Japanese 9.7, the French 9.3, and the Canadians 9.2. The Americans
outscored only the Italians at 7.6 and the Mexicans at 7.4.
   Now it appears that same test is coming to the Soviet Union.
Izvestia said the planned poll is a joint project of Gallup and the
National Geographic Society aimed at determining the level of
geographic knowledge of various countries.
   Although the Soviets have broken with tradition and started their
own public opinion polls in the past year, this apparently is the
first time a foreign firm will be permitted to conduct a survey on
Soviet soil, albeit in conjunction with the Soviet Institute for
Sociological Research.
   For many years, sociology was a lost science in the Soviet Union,
as Marxist-Leninism claims all societies will inevitably develop
into communism.
   Personal thoughts were grounds for imprisonment, and public
opinion polls were inconceivable.
   Maps are still sketchy and deliberately distorted, with rivers
shifted and whole sections of major cities excised. The government
admitted to that practice several months ago and promised that
accurate maps were forthcoming. Many Soviet citizens have difficulty
reading maps as a result of these inaccuracies.
   Reliance on public transportation is also limits some citizens'
sense of direction.
   ``Follow bus No. 7,'' may be the best advice a motorist can
expect.
   Americans, however, don't fare much better, according to Gallup.
More than one-third could not pick out the westernmost city on a
simple map, its U.S. poll found.
   The Gallup poll also will survey Soviet consumers to determine
what products they buy and what items they would like to purchase,
Izvestia said.
   That basic marketing question may sound a bit strange to Soviet
ears. With a chronic severe shortage of nearly all consumer items,
most Soviet consumers buy anything decent they find, regardless of
such niceties as size, and then trade with friends.
   The Gallup poll also will question Soviet consumers' familiarity
with American-made products, Izvestia said.
   Soviets love Western brand names and snap up shirts, stickers,
hats, almost anything imprinted with names like Addidas, Nike and
Mercedes. But the genuine Western products are hard to come by, as
the Soviet Union has cut imports of consumer goods as its foreign
income has fallen with the price of Siberian oil and gas.
   Exact wording of the Gallup survey questions is still being
worked out, but it should be completed by mid-January, Izvestia said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1414EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ForcedLanding 5thLd-Writethru a0575 12-26 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forced Landing, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0575,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hole In Fuselage Forces Airliner To Land</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs with officials now CORRECTING that hole 14
inches, sted 18 inches, spokeswoman calling it a tear, age of plane;
Picks up 6th graf, `Passenger Sam ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines jet with 110 people
aboard made an emergency landing today after a 14-inch hole
developed in the fuselage and the cabin lost compression at 31,000
feet, authorities said.
   The Boeing 727, which was flying from Rochester, N.Y., to
Atlanta, landed safely and none of the 104 passengers or six crew
members aboard Flight 251 was injured, said Yeager Airport Police
Chief Robert Barnette.
   The tear was on the top of the fuselage over the last rows of the
20-year-old jet, said Karen Ceremsak, an Eastern spokeswoman in
Miami.
   The plane experienced no sudden trouble when the hole opened up,
except the ``rapid decompression,'' and flew on for another 50
miles, said Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Jack Barker in
Atlanta.
   The passengers put on their oxygen masks, and the pilot simply
``flew it to 10,000 feet,'' an altitude that requires no
pressurization in the cabin, Barker said.
   Passenger Sam Piazza, 55, of Boca Raton, Fla., said at first he
and his wife thought a bomb had exploded.
   ``We were cruising along and you could hear the rush of the wind
and the pitch of the wind and all of a sudden you could hear a big
pop,'' Piazza said.
   Bill Tretter, 25, of Buffalo, N.Y., and three family members were
waiting for lunch when the cabin lost pressure.
   ``We were just going along, and they were serving the first-class
passengers and all of a sudden air started to rush by and it was
kicking up dust,'' Tretter said.
   All 104 passengers planned to continue on to Atlanta, Barker
said. There was no immediate indication of the cause of the crack,
he said.
   Barnette said he received the first report of the emergency
landing request at 9:10 a.m.
   ``As far as I was concerned it was a normal landing, I asked if
he needed assistance and he said no. There was no emergency crews
needed on the runway,'' said the air traffic controller who guided
the plane in. He refused to be identified.
   The roof of a Boeing 737 was torn off during an Aloha Airlines
flight on April 28, killing one person and injuring 61 others. The
accident prompted a federal investigation into the aging fleet of
jets. The FAA ordered airlines to replace rivets believed to have
caused cracks in the fuselage skin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0097 </DOCNO>
