<2ND_LINE>AM-Namibia,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Leader Says Military Success Brought Namibian Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos
Santos says his country's military successes against South Africa
led to the signing of Namibia's independence agreement, according to
a report received here Monday.
   ANGOP, Angola's state news agency, said dos Santos praised the
Angolan armed forces during a ceremony Sunday when he received
copies of the treaties signed in New York on Thursday by Angola,
Cuba and South Africa.
   There was no mention in the report about the agreement for the
withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola as a link to South
African withdrawal from neighboring Namibia, which South Africa has
ruled for 73 years.
   The ANGOP report quoted dos Santos as saying his government
forces made an ``incalculable contribution to the cause of peace.''
   He declared they won the October 1987 battle for Cuito Cuanavale
city, ``the largest military battle ever fought in sub-Saharan
Africa.'' The report did not indicate whether he mentioned Cubans
who supported Angolan troops in the battle or the participation of
guerrillas opposed to his government who reportedly still are
fighting at Cuito Cuanavale.
   The strategic town in southern Angola was beseiged by South
African forces and guerrillas of Jonas Savimbi's National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola. Dos Santos said they never managed
to capture the town.
   Savimbi said he did not want to occupy the town, but forced
Angolan forces to abandon it and a plan to attack his headquarters
at Jamba.
   Dos Santos was quoted as saying the defense of Cuito Cuanavale
and ensuing military successes achieved with Cuban soldiers at
Ruacana and Calueque _ where many South African soldiers guarding
dam installations were killed _ ``have changed the direction of
events in southern Africa, and led the parties involved to
negotiation.''
   The New York accords ``open the path to peace in southern Africa,
since they have made inevitable a search for a political solution to
the grave problem of apartheid in South Africa,'' he said.
</TEXT>
