<HEAD>Utility To File Bankruptcy Plan Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Company of New Hampshire, the
first major investor-owned utility to seek bankruptcy protection
since the Depression, must file its reorganization plan with a
federal judge Tuesday.
   The utility has said it probably will seek federal regulation
enabling it to charge its 360,000 ratepayers for its 36 percent
share in the stalled $5.7 billion Seabrook nuclear plant.
   State law bars charging ratepayers before a plant is operating.
   The reactor was completed in 1986 but has not been able to
receive a license of evacuation planning obstacles.
   The utility has said it may be entitled to rate increases of up
to 40 percent over two years under federal regulation. The state
reportedly offered rate increases of at least 4 percent a year for
five years.
   Four New England utilities have expressed interest in taking over
some or all of Public Service's non-Seabrook assets.
