<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ArabLeague     12-26 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arab League,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab League Warns United States against Military Strike on Libya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League Council on Monday said the
United States risks ``serious repercussions'' in its relations with
the Arab world if it attacks Libya.
   The final resolution of a special session called by Libya said an
international organization was best suited to examine the U.S.
complaint that Libya maintains a chemical weapons factory.
   ``The council considers the American threats as a factor of
tension itself threatening the international climate of detente and
peace that Arab states are trying to support and consolidate,'' read
the resolution, which was unanimously adopted.
   President Reagan, in a television interview last week, said
Washington has been discussing with its allies the possibility of
taking military action to destroy a Libyan factory it claims can
produce enormous quantities of chemical weapons.
   U.S. spokesmen have said military action was only one of several
options.
   Libya denies the charge, says the factory is producing
pharmaceuticals and declared its ``full commitment to all
international conventions'' banning chemical weapons.
   Also on Monday, Kuwait joined Iran, Iraq, Syria and the Palestine
Liberation Organization in pledging to back Libya in the event of a
U.S. attack.
   ``These threats are not directed against Libya alone but against
the entire Arab world,'' Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Ahmed told the
Kuwait News Agency. ``Kuwait stands by sister Libya against any
aggression it might confront.''
   The Arab League resolution said questions, ``in particular those
of a military character,'' should be submitted to competent
international organizations such as the United Nations and the
International Atomic Energy Agency.
   U.S. spokesmen have said they would like the issue examined at an
international conference in Paris Jan. 7-11 to consider ways of
enforcing the 1925 Geneva convention outlawing chemical weapons.
   The resolution reaffirmed the Arab League's solidarity with Libya
and warned the United States that ``any attempt at an aggression
against this state risks the most serious repercussions in the
region and in Arab-American relations.''
   It further accused Israel of using chemical weapons in southern
Lebanon and the occupied territories.
   The council ``notes with surprise the silence of the United
States'' in the face of Israel's use and ``fabrication and stockage
of these prohibited arms,'' it said.
   No one has made such accusations before. The Israeli government
customarily refuses to confirm or deny foreign reports that it
started to develop chemical arms after Egypt used such weapons
during its 1963-67 involvement in the civil war in Yemen.
   Israeli leaders have vowed to retaliate ``thousandfold'' in the
event of a chemical attack from the Arab side.
   Arab League Secretary-General Chedli Klibi, opening the special
session, accused Washington of violating the U.N. charter and
international law with its threat.
   ``The new threats proffered by the United States evoke the
astonishment of the Arab states and are denounced by our peoples,''
Klibi said. ``They show, what's more, the seriousness of a situation
where a state, no matter how important it is, treats questions of
international conflict outside the framework of the United Nations,
the only appropriate framework.
   ``The Arab states warn against the inherent risks of the American
accusations and against all aggression against one of them.''
   U.S. warplanes bombed Libya in 1986 in retaliation for the
terrorist attack on a West Berlin disco where two U.S. servicemen
and a Turkish woman were killed and more than 200 soldiers and
others were injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
