<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     12-26 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Daily Calls for Government to Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leading Communist Party daily on
Monday called on Parliament to replace Premier Branko Mikulic and
his government because of failure to resolve Yugoslavia's worst
postwar economic crisis.
   ``Mikulic's government must fall because it was not able to carry
out its own programs and to create a climate for an authentic start
of economic reforms,'' said the daily Borba in a front-page
editorial.
   Yugoslavia is grappling with a 250 percent annual inflation rate,
15 percent unemployment, a $21 billion foreign debt and growing
labor unrest.
   ``The Yugoslav Parliament should usher in the new year by
replacing the current federal government,'' Borba said.
   Mikulic, who came to power in 1986, indicated in a recent
interview that he and his government had no intention of resigning.
No government or premier has resigned or been replaced in Yugoslavia
since the communists came to power after World War II.
   Borba said that if the government is not replaced, Yugoslavia
might be faced with severe labor unrest.
   In 1988, workers staged a record 1,000 strikes to protest low
wages and plunging living standards that have dropped to the
mid-1960s level, according to official statistics.
   ``The patience of the Yugoslav working class is running low,''
Borba said.
   In another development, a former official was expelled from the
Communist Party on Monday for his alleged involvement in a
real-estate scandal in the central republic of Bosnia, the official
Tanjug news agency reported.
   A party disciplinary commission expelled Todo Kurtovic for using
political influence to secure favorable bank loans to build a
luxurious vacation home on the central Adriatic coast.
   Kurtovic came to prominence as of the party's top ideologues in
the 1970s, when he headed the communist-led Socialist Alliance and
authored books on socialism.
   The Parliament of Bosna demanded last week that legislation be
passed allowing authorities to confiscate homes belonging to several
hundred Bosnian politicians who obtained illegal bank loans to build
them.
   They include Milanko Renovica, until last year president of the
party's ruling Politburo, and Nikola Stojanovic, a former member of
the Politburo.
   Mikulic, who is from Bosnia, has also been linked to the
real-estate scandal, but the premier last week denied repeated
allegations that he owned illegally-financed property in Bosnia.
   According to press reports, Bosnian politicians qualified for the
loans by having local banks order a temporary transfer of foreign
currency from the accounts of Yugoslavs working abroad to the
applicant's account. The foreign currency served as collateral to
secure the loan, and would then be returned to the original
accounts. Such services were repaid with political favors and rapid
promotions, according to the reports.
   The terms of the loans did not include the usual adjustments for
inflation, thus reducing the real value of the mortgage to what one
press report called ``the value of a pack of cigarettes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
