<HEAD>PLO Executive Committee Concludes Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat and his top aides
concluded a three-day meeting Monday focused on means of advancing
the peace process in the Middle East, a PLO official said.
   One development reported from the 15-member PLO Executive
Committee meeting was a decision to upgrade the status of PLO
offices to embassies in countries that have recognized the
independent Palestinian state. Ninety countries have recognized the
state so far, officials said.
   Azzam Al-Ahmed, director of the Palestine Liberation Organization
office in Baghdad, said the leaders discussed a host of issues
during five closed-door sessions, including the latest dialogue with
the United States, the formation of a provisional government in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and the year-old uprising
there.
   Al-Ahmed would not specify on any conclusions, saying a statement
would be issued later.
   Sources close to the executive committee said Sunday the members
agreed that in further talks with the United States, the PLO should
stress greater U.S. recognition of the group and the need for an
international peace conference.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the PLO
will urge the United States to recognize it as the sole and
legitimate representative of the Palestinian people.
   Earlier this month, Washington broke a 13-year ban on contacts
with the PLO. Talks were held in Tunis, Tunisia several days later.
   The committee also broached the topic of forming a provisional
government, a Palestinian spokesman said. He said the issue needed
further discussion.
   Arafat was quoted Monday as telling the West German magazine
Spiegel that an independent Palestinian state must have a corridor
through Israel connecting the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In November, the Palestine National Council, the PLO's
parliament-in-exile, declared an independent Palestinian state but
did not specify its borders.
   ``We can negotiate over that in the peace conference,'' Arafat
was quoted as telling Spiegel of the borders.
   ``But in all cases we will insist on establishing a corridor
between West Jordan (the West Bank) and the Gaza Strip. It is not
acceptable for us to establish a state split into two parts,''
Spiegel quoted Arafat as saying.
</TEXT>
