<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Quake     12-26 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Quake,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snowstorm Cuts Off Roads Into Armenian Earthquake Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A raging snowstorm cut off roads into the
quake-devastated area of Armenia on Monday, leaving survivors and
emergency workers shivering in tents and the unheated shells of
buildings, the government newspaper Izvestia reported.
   Freezing temperatures dropped sharply and were expected to reach
5 degrees, Soviet television reported. Campfires and emergency
stoves provided the only warmth. The heating plants that produce
steam for the radiators of entire Soviet cities were destroyed in
the Dec. 7 earthquake, which authorities say killed up to 55,000
people.
   Survivors continued to search for missing relatives among the
dead, the injured, and the displaced.
   One widowed father tracked down his infant son, who was five days
old when the quake smashed the Leninakan maternity hospital where he
was born and killed everyone but that one baby boy. Dug from the
ruins after being buried for two days and nights, the infant was
still wearing a wrist name tag, Tass reported.
   The father of little Oganez Gevorkyan found him in a Yerevan
hospital, suffering from a broken arm and a broken leg.
   ``The father stood a long time over the cot, tears coursing down
his face,'' Tass said. And then the elder Gevorkyan hastened back to
his army unit to continue clearing earthquake debris. The Soviet
news agency did not give the father's first name.
   Another Armenian man by the name of Arutyunyan dashed into a
collapsing maternity hospital and saved his wife and newborn son.
The quake slammed into their village of Nalband, right at the
epicenter, just as the boy was born, knocking him out of the
obstetrician's hands and leaving the exhausted new mother to pick
him up.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda reported Monday that Moscow
is cracking down on party leaders in neighboring Azerbaijan who
failed to cool flaming tempers and ethnic violence, which led tens
of thousands of Armenians to flee Azerbaijan in the weeks before the
quake. An undetermined number of refugees settled in with relatives
in the quake area just before the earthquake struck.
   A military patrol halted the fleeing Communist Party chief of the
Kedabak region only after firing on his automobile, Pravda said. The
soldiers found him carrying cash amounting to several years' salary,
Pravda said.
   In Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan, 213 party members were
disciplined for failing to ease tension, Pravda said. Thirteen were
expelled from the party. In another group, 121 persons held
responsible were fired from their jobs.
   Pravda blamed criminal elements and their government protectors
for inciting the ethnic strife as a cover-up for their activities.
Moscow has sent hundreds of special prosecutors into the area to
investigate charges of corruption.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
