<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0594 12-26 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President-elect Praises Son's Trip To Armenia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: ```Jeb and...'' to make it ``Jeb
said''; SUBS 10th graf pvs, bgng: ``Bush said...'' to reflect
Jonathan Bush's plans to visit; picks up 11th graf pvs, bgng:
``Bush, who...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEEVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush, beginning a four-day
hunting and fishing vacation Monday, called his son Jeb's visit to
earthquake victims in Soviet Armenia ``so moving and so right.''
   Bush flew to this rural south Texas town about 70 miles from
Corpus Christi to hunt quail on the secluded 10,000-acre Lazy-F
ranch owned by his long-time friend, Will Farish, a Houston
investmant banker.
   Looking casual and relaxed in a red shirt and black cowboy boots,
Bush told reporters his best Christmas present was seeing Jeb, a
Miami real estate developer, and his grandson, George, 12, deliver
toys and medical supplies to children in Yerevan, Armenia on
Christmas Day.
   ``It was so moving and so right ... it said what we feel ... we
want to reach out to those others less fortunate,'' Bush said.
   The vice president, arriving at Chase Naval Air Station in the
flat Texas scrubland, said he talked with Jeb by telephone as the
younger Bushes flew back to the United States.
   Jeb said the trip was ``probably the most moving thing he has
ever been involved in,'' Bush recounted.
   The Soviet ambassador to the United States, Yuri Dubinin, was
also ``deeply appreciative'' of the efforts Jeb Bush and other
Americans are making to help victims of the earthquake that killed
about 50,000 people, Bush said.
   Jeb Bush flew to Armenia aboard a cargo plane chartered by
Americares, a relief agency, to deliver toys and medical supplies to
children on Christmas Day.
   The president-elect spent Christmas in Washington with his wife,
Barbara, and one of his five children, Marvin, and his wife and
daughter. Mrs. Bush did not accompany her husband on the trip to
Texas, an annual ritual Bush has followed for two decades.
   Bush said his designated secretary of state, James Baker III, and
Mrs. Baker are planning to visit the Farish ranch, possibly arriving
Monday night. In addition, Bush's brother, Jonathan, was expected to
join the group.
   Bush, who doesn't have a heavy work schedule for the next four
days, said he ``brought a little homework, a little inaugural
backround material, a little reading,'' especially on the budget.
   ``Everything has to fit into a budget plan,'' he said.
   While saying he has no qualms about hunting birds, Bush said, ``I
don't think I could shoot a deer. ... Quail hunting, that is
something else again.''
   ``These aren't animals ... These are wild quail,'' he said. ``Our
forefathers ate by harvesting game.''
   On Saturday, Bush named the 13th person to his Cabinet, Elizabeth
Dole as labor secretary. The only high-level job vacancies that
remain are for energy secretary and the newly created drug czar
post. Bush said there would be no announcements before Friday at the
earliest.
   After his vacation, Bush intends to focus on legislative and
policy issues.
   He said he will sit down with ``our education people,'' with
William Reilly, nominated as head of the Environmental Protection
Agency, and Attorney General Dick Thornburgh with whom the
president-elect wants to review anti-crime and anti-drug programs.
   Bush was asked about the investigation into the crash of the Pam
American flight over England last week. There was been speculation a
bomb might have caused the explosion.
   Bush said there was some ``interesting speculation,'' about the
crash, but he had no information about the investigation.
   He also said he would he would ``get on that plane right now'' if
he thought his precence in the Middle East would bring about peace.
But such diplomatic initiatives must be planned, Bush said, adding
he is not yet president.
   Asked about Egyptian Presiident Hosni Mubarak's offer to visit
Israel, Bush responded: ``The more contact they have ... the better
it is.''
   On Thursday, Bush leaves Beeville to fly to Alabama where he will
spend a few hours fishing before he returns to the nation's capital.
   Bush will fish for bass in a 55-acre lake on the property of Ray
Scott, president of Bass Anglers Sportsmen's Society. The lake is in
Pintlalla, near Montgomery.
</TEXT>
