<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionFires     12-26 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Fires,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Activist Condemns Abortion Clinic Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of an anti-abortion organization Monday
denounced the setting of fires at three clinics on Christmas morning.
   ``I think if it was in fact people doing this in the name of
right to life, they've done our movement no favors at all,'' said
Bill Price, head of the Texas Coalition for Life and president of
the Greater Dallas Right ot Life Committee. ``We just do not in any
form or fashion condone this type of activity.''
   A to Z Women's Health Services, the Fairmont Center and the North
Dallas Women's Clinic sustained minor damage in the fires, which
were reported early Sunday within about a half hour, investigators
said. No injuries were reported.
   Clinic officials charged the attacks are the work of
anti-abortion groups, which have staged protests and ``baby
rescues'' at the clinics in the past year.
   ``They are definitely suspicious fires,'' said Fire Capt. Mike
Southerland. ``It's possible some flammable liquids were used, but I
don't know what types at this time.''
   The U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms also is
investigating for links to past attacks on abortion clinics.
   ``I think all these fires were definitely connected,'' said Dena
Jackson, director of operations at North Dallas Women's clinic.
``When you look at the people that are anti-choice, they tend to be
highly religious. And with Christmas Day being so significant, I
think that definitely had something to do with it also.''
   ``We feel like we know who it is,'' agreed Betty Pettigrew,
director of A to Z Women's Health Services. ``They're always
threatening it, and we had heard that some clinic was going to be
hit _ not necessarily in Dallas.''
   Price said the fires improperly move the focus of the
right-to-life cause away from its goal and place it on the arson
controversy.
</TEXT>
