<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0596 12-26 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0596,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Experts Examine Wreckage; Looting Suspect Arrested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Deputy Chief ... UPDATING with bodies to
be
released Tuesday. Picks up 6th One more ...; SUBS grafs 18-19 pvs,
The Rev. ... CORRECTING name from Keegan to Keegans. Picks up 20th
``Confronted with ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LOCK3, LON5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associatd Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military explosives experts will
examine a suitcase from Pan Am Flight 103 and pieces of the
shattered jumbo jet for evidence of a bomb, Britain's top
investigator at the scene said Monday.
   At a news conference, however, a spokeswoman for investigator
Michael Charles refused to say where the suitcase was found, whether
it was intact or what attracted attention to it.
   Penny Russell-Smith, a Department of Transport press officer,
would only add that the suitcase ``exhibited characteristics which
merit further consideration.''
   For the first time since the crash Wednesday, police were
preparing to release the bodies of victims after pathologists
completed post mortems and confirmed identification.
   Police said about half a dozen bodies would be released Tuesday,
but Deputy Chief Constable Paul Newall said he could not provide
names or nationalities.
   One more body was found Monday, raising the total of bodies found
to 240. Police also announced the arrest of a local man following a
report of looting at a crash site.
   At least 29 bodies are still missing from the 258 people who died
aboard the New York-bound Boeing 747. Steady rains throughout most
of the day and low clouds restricted the search, Newall said.
   ``There may be some we will not find, and I think everyone should
be aware of that,'' Newall said.
   Police spokesman Angus Kennedy said Monday that all the occupants
of four cars found near one crash site had been found alive. Eleven
townspeople are missing and feared dead.
   Ms. Russell-Smith refused to say any more about the suitcase, nor
would she describe the amount of wreckage submitted for analysis or
what part of the aircraft it came from.
   ``Although, because of the fragmented and scattered nature of the
wreckage the investigation of the structural aspects of the accident
is a slow process, no evidence of a structural failure has so far
been found,'' Charles said in a statement released in Lockerbie and
in London by the Department of Transport.
   ``However, the possibility of such a failure is still being
actively investigated,'' Charles said. ``Some pieces of wreckage and
a suitcase are today being taken to the Royal Armament Research and
Development Establishment at Fort Halstead in Kent for more detailed
examination to determine whether they exhibit evidence of a
pre-impact explosion.''
   The Defense Department said the center does research on
explosives and armor.
   Experts have said structural failure or a bomb are the most
likely reasons the Pan Am jet disappeared from radar screens just as
it reached cruising altitude of 31,000 feet over southwestern
Scotland.
   The Times of London quoted William Tench, former chief inspector
of air accidents, as saying he believed a structural failure caused
the crash.
   The flight originated as a Boeing 727 from Frankfurt, West
Germany, with a change of planes at London's Heathrow International
Airport. Federal police in West Germany and the commander of
Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist squad last week began investigations
at those airports.
   Newall said he believed the looting case was an isolated
incident. It occurred in the area where falling wreckage exploded in
a fireball, obliterating four houses and severely damaging 20
others. All the missing townspeople were residents of the
neighborhood.
   The Rev. Patrick Keegans, the Roman Catholic parish priest, lost
his home in that neighborhood, although he was away from it at the
time.
   At a Requiem Mass Monday night, Keegans spoke of the bewilderment
of those who lost loved ones.
   ``Confronted with the horror of such loss, we feel empty, hurt,
confused, and we say to ourselves, `things will never be the same
again.' As Christ did on the Cross, we too scream at the Father, `My
God, my God, why have you abandoned me?' He does not seem to answer.
There is only silence.''
   Britain's Independent Television Network canceled plans to cover
the Mass after Kennedy said several relatives of the dead indicated
they would not attend a televised service. At least 90 relatives,
mostly from the United States, are known to have visited the town
since the crash.
   Lockerbie's streets were quiet and its shops were closed Monday
for Boxing Day, a holiday in Britain's long Christmas break.
   Social workers expressed concern about the delayed effects of the
disaster on the town's 2,500 residents.
   Leslie Jardine, a spokesman for the local social work department,
said a brochure advertising a telephone hotline was being
distributed to every home.
   ``Nature heals through allowing these feelings to come out,'' the
brochure said. ``Stopping these feelings may lead to nervous and
physical problems. Crying gives relief.''
</TEXT>
