<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1810EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewBedfordHeroin     12-26 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Bedford Heroin,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Bedford Murders Not First Spate of Death Linked to Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The slayings of six women in recent
months have diverted attention from another killer that has stalked
this seaport for more than two years _ high-purity heroin.
   City Medical Examiner Dr. John O'Toole III estimated he handles
between 30 and 40 overdose deaths per year in the greater New
Bedford area.
   ``When I first joined the force you'd see heroin 5, 10 percent
pure. Now it's 50 to 60 percent pure,'' said Detective Richard
Spirlet.
   The potent heroin, bearing labels like Supra 87 and Power 95, has
drawn far less attention than the unknown killer responsible for the
slayings of six women whose bodies were found along highways in this
part of Massachusetts.
   When Mayor John Bullard was asked about the impact of the
slayings on the community he spoke not of the fear of murder but of
the scourge of drug addiction in this city of 98,000 about 50 miles
south of Boston.
   ``The biggest problem is the waste of human lives that takes
place off the front pages,'' Bullard said. Law enforcement
authorities said is no accident that the one thing all the murder
victims had in common was drug abuse.
   New Bedford, home of the state's largest methadone program, has
become a bustling retail outlet for heroin coming in by car from New
York City and Providence, R.I.
   A large Colombian population in nearby Central Falls, R.I., has
kept New Bedford well stocked in cocaine, according to law
enforcement officials.
   In August, September and October the city Emergency Medical
Services were responding to 17 overdose calls a month. In November,
when the discovery of the bodies became a major news story, there
were 29 ambulance runs for overdoses.
   ``I think the reason they overdose is they really don't know what
they're getting,'' said Kenneth Sylvia, deputy director of the
emergency medical services unit. ``A person is immune to a certain
percentage of heroin. If they go over that, they overdose and I know
that because I had a sister who overdosed and died.''
   New Bedford boasts the nation's richest fishing port in the
dollar value of its catch but has higher-than-average unemployment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
