<DOCNO> AP881226-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1816EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uruguay     12-26 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uruguay,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Referendum on Amnesty Law Approved; Vote Probably in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL GIANELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Electoral Court confirmed on
Monday that enough Uruguayans signed petitions opposing a December
1986 military amnesty law to force a referendum that could overturn
it.
   The referendum probably will be held in April, said Juan Furest,
one of the nine members of the court. The exact date will be
disclosed within 10 days.
   Foes of the amnesty law needed 555,701 signatures, representing
one-quarter of Uruguay's 2.2 million electorate, to obtain a
referendum and Furest said they obtained the required number.
   The amnesty law bars the prosecution of soldiers and police
accused of human rights abuses, including murder, committed during
the 1973-85 military dictatorship's suppression of urban terrorism.
   Local human rights groups said about 150 Uruguayans were killed,
200 were arrested and disappeared, and thousands were tortured in
this small South American nation of 3 million people.
   President Julio M. Sanguinetti opposes the referendum and
predicts the amnesty law will not be overturned. He says overturning
the law carries the likelihood of a ``long, hazardous . .. and
dramatic period of confrontation'' between soldiers and civilians.
   The law was passed as civil courts were about call military
officers to answer charges of murder, kidnapping and torture.
Officers indicated they would ignore requests to testify, setting up
a potential clash with the government.
   The same issue in Argentina has led to three unsuccessful
military insurrections there in the past 20 months against the
government of President Raul Alfonsin.
   Sanguinetti, elected in November 1984, took office in March 1985.
</TEXT>
