<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ColdResearch     12-26 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cold Research,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Weather Reseach Center Proposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rudy Perpich wants to
spend $2.2 million to take advantage of this community's reputation
as the ``nation's icebox.''
   The money would be used to lure companies here to do mechanical
testing and help them promote their products as having withstood the
lowest temperatures in the lower 48 states.
   ``International Falls is a cold place. So is Minnesota. Why not
'fess up to it and capitalize on it?'' said Richard Braun, chairman
of the Governor's Commission on Cold Weather Research.
   The governor said he will include the request in his 1989 budget
proposal.
   Companies such as Ford Motor Co. and Bell Helicopters already do
mechanical testing here.
   Testing and related activity pump about $300,000 a year into the
economy of the community, which is seeking a sister-city
relationship with a Siberian village that gets so cold that milk is
sold in frozen blocks.
</TEXT>
