<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1823EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0589 12-26 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0589,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Reported Seeking U.S. and Soviet-Sponsored Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 2nd graf pvs, Shamir's proposal ...
UPDATING with Bush reaaction. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Ahimeir said .
.. with minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir may ask the United
States and the Soviet Union to sponsor Middle East peace talks as
part of his new peace initiative, an aide said Monday.
   Shamir's proposal, confirmed by his spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir,
came as Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak was reported to be
considering a trip to Israel to advance stalemated peace efforts.
   In Beeville, Texas, President-elect Bush expressed support Monday
for a meeting between Egyptian and Israeli leaders, saying, ``The
more contact they have ... the better it is.'' He said in response
to a question he, too, would be willing to go to the Middle East if
he believed it would further the peace process.
   Ahimeir said in a telephone interview that Shamir would condition
his proposal on Moscow's renewing diplomatic ties. The Kremlin
severed ties with Israel during the 1967 Middle East War, when
Israel captured Arab lands.
   Mubarak was quoted in an interview with a Kuwaiti newspaper
Sunday as saying he would go to Israel if the visit would help
achieve peace. It would be the first visit to the Jewish state by an
Arab leader since the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat made his
last trip in September 1979.
   Shamir has said he would welcome a visit by Mubarak.
   ``He would like to renew the link with Mubarak,'' Ahimeir said,
adding that the timing seemed right since Shamir, as leader of the
right-wing Likud bloc, took office for a second straight term
Thursday.
   The Likud virtually has complete control over the nation's
foreign policy, although the left-leaning Labor Party is still in
the government. Labor's leader Shimon Peres, formerly foreign
minister, is now finance minister.
   Israel's ambassador in Cairo, Shimon Shamir, was meeting with
Egyptian officials to determine whether a Mubarak visit was
possible, said another Shamir spokesman, Avi Pazner.
   Thomas Pickering, the outgoing U.S. ambassador to Israel who has
been named U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, told reporters in
Tel Aviv a Shamir-Mubarak summit was ``certainly something the U.S.
would encourage and welcome.''
   He said the United States also was encouraged by Israeli efforts
to come up with a new peace initiative despite its fierce opposition
to recent U.S. contacts with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Shamir has been drawing up his own peace plans as alternatives to
growing pressure on Israel to negotiate with the PLO and participate
in a proposed international Middle East peace conference.
   Israel rejects any dialogue with the PLO, which it considers a
terrorist group. Shamir also has refused calls to join an
international conference, fearing a wide forum of nations would be
biased against Israel and pressure it to concede land to the Arabs.
   Ahimeir said that according to Shamir's proposal, the two
superpowers would ``invite the parties of the conflict to sit down
and negotiate'' without the participation of other U.N. Security
Council members.
   The daily newspaper Maariv said Monday that in talks with
Mubarak, Shamir would propose an Egyptian role in getting
negotiations started between Israel and a delegation made up of
Palestinians and representatives from neighboring Jordan.
   The aim of such talks would be to reach an interim agreement for
Palestinian self-rule in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, the
newspaper said.
   Ahimeir said Shamir would be willing to coax Jordan into peace
talks by agreeing to consider modifications of the U.S.-sponsored
Camp David Accords signed in 1978, which led to an Israeli-Egyptian
peace treaty the following year.
   ``We want to get the Jordanians into the peace circle. We will
start with Camp David and are ready to discuss any changes they
want. We will listen and discuss it with them,'' Ahimeir said. He
declined to elaborate.
   Both Jordan and the PLO have in the past rejected the Camp David
accords, which outline a five-year autonomy or self-rule plan for
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip pending negotiations
for a final settlement.
   Although Israel wants Jordan to be a peace partner, King Hussein
distanced himself from that role in July when he severed his ties
with the West Bank.
   Palestinians in the occupied lands have been protesting Israel
rule there for more than a year in what has been called the
``intefadeh,'' or uprising. On Monday, soldiers shot and wounded
eight Palestinians in scattered clashes in the territories.
   At least 336 Palestinians and 14 Israelis have died since the
uprising began Dec. 8, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
