<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Castro-Referendum 1stLd-Writethru a0619 12-26 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Castro-Referendum, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers, Artists Aks Cuban Leader For Referendum On His Rule</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to ADD detail on human rights
committee, areas of expertise of Nobel laureates. PICKS up 4th graf
`The letter...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 writers, artists and
scientists have sent an open letter to Cuban President Fidel Castro
asking him to hold a referendum on extending his rule, a Cuban
activist said Monday.
   The signatories from the United States, Europe, and Latin America
also include 50 exiled Cubans, said physician Marta Freyde. She
lives in Madrid and serves as vice-president of the Human Rights
Committee in Cuba, an independent group.
   Among those who signed were Italian film director Federico
Fellini; French actor Yves Montand; Nobel Prize-winning writers
Claude Simon and Saul Bellow and scientists Andre Lwoff and Jean
Dausset; and writers Camilo Jose Cela of Spain, Octavio Paz of
Mexico, Ernesto Sabato of Argentina, and Mario Vargas LLosa of Peru,
Ms. Freyde said.
   The letter notes that Jan. 1, 1989, marks the 30th anniversary of
Castro's communist rule and says he never has asked the Cuban people
to give him a mandate through a vote.
   The message calls for a ``free and secret vote.'' It also asks
that Cuban exiles and government opponents be allowed to return so
they can publicly campaign; release of all political prisoners;
legalization of human rights committees, and creation of an
independent body to supervise voting.
   The signatories point to an October plesbiscite in Chile ``where
the people, after 15 years of dictatorship, have been able to freely
express their country's political future.'' Chilean voters rejected
extending the term of military President Augusto Pinochet until 1997.
</TEXT>
