<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush Son Returns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Son, Grandson Back from Armenia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS time element to Saturday sted Friday in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY48</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush's son and grandson
returned to the United States from earthquake-stricken Armenia on
Monday, with the younger Bush saying the visit enabled him to feel
the real meaning of Christmas.
   John E. Bush and his son, George, 12, had flown to the Armenian
capital of Yerevan on a relief flight Saturday. They toured the
disaster zone in a bus, stopping at a children's hospital to deliver
candy bars and gifts.
   ``I think we did some good for our country,'' the elder Bush said
at John F. Kennedy International Airport. Of the earthquake victims,
he said, ``We're doing good for them in a specific way, so I was
privileged.''
   Bush, 35, a Miami real estate developer, stopped with his son in
Spitak, which was destroyed by the earthquake Dec. 7.
   ``We'd seen it on television every night, but to be there is
different, I think more profound,'' he said. ``We take for granted a
very good life.''
   ``It was very sad to see these kids my age'' in the hospital,
said his son. He said he thought they ``were happy to get presents
from a person from across the world.''
   The younger Bush said he hadn't minded spending his Christmas
away from home. ``Many people think Christmas Day is a day when you
open presents. But it's to celebrate Jesus' birth,'' he said. ``I
had the Christmas spirit.''
   Their flight was organized by Americares, a relief organization
in New Canaan, Conn. Steve Johnson, a vice president of Americares,
said the flight carried about $3 million in supplies, mostly medical.
   Bush said he returned with a list of needs given him by an
Armenian church official, including medicine and computer equipment
   An estimated 55,000 people were killed in the earthquake and half
a million were left homeless.
</TEXT>
