<HEAD>27 Stricken With Food Poisoning After Christmas Dinner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-seven residents of a drug rehabilitation
center were stricken with apparent food poisoning after a Christmas
dinner, but none required hospitalization, officials said.
   Thirteen of the Phoenix House residents were treated and released
at hospitals early Monday. City paramedics treated 14 at the center.
   Health Department officials took samples of the food that was
served to the 250 residents, but had not determined the problem,
said center spokesman Christopher Policano.
   The menu included turkey and trimmings, chicken, ham, greens, egg
nog and pie.
   The residents complained of nausea, vomiting and diarrhea,
Policano said.
