<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HuntSaboteurs     12-26 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunt Saboteurs,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Activists Try To Disrupt Fox Hunts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal rights activists turned out in force Monday
to try to disrupt fox hunters and prevent the killing of their
quarry.
   All around the country, packs of dogs and red-coated riders
thundered across fields and over fences in pursuit of foxes, as they
always do on Boxing Day, a nationwide holiday the day after
Christmas.
   The Hunt Saboteurs' Association, marking its 25th year of
anti-hunt activities, was out in the field too _ laying false trails
and using their own hunting horns to try to confuse the dogs.
   Placard-waving activists confronted the Surrey Union Hunt in
Guildford, south of London, and scores of hunt saboteurs mingled
with onlookers and booed, shouted and chanted ``Scum'' as the
hunters clattered down the town's cobbled high street on their sleek
horses.
   Supporters carried placards reading: ``Stop this bloody cruelty''
and ``Hunting is a crime not a sport.''
   In Mortimer, Berkshire, southwest of London, police moved in when
activists became involved in angry exchanges with members and
followers of the Garth and South Berks Hunt. Three men were arrested
after the reins of one of the horses were cut, police said. Two were
charged with breach of the peace and the third was being questioned
about alleged criminal damage.
   Police reported angry scenes between hunt supporters and animal
rights activists at the start of the Albrighton Hunt meet at Hagley,
Worcester, in central England.
   A police spokesman, speaking anonymously, said a hunt saboteur
spattered several people with fake blood but there was no serious
trouble and no arrests were made.
</TEXT>
