<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrainDerailment 1stLd-Writethru a0625 12-26 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0625,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spread Rails Thought To Be Cause Of Zephyr Derailment That Stranded
300</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT in editor's note that erroneous
reference was to warped tracks sted derailment</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GLENWOOD SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators were trying to
determine Monday what caused an 18-car passenger train to jump the
tracks, stranding nearly 300 holiday travelers overnight but
injuring no one, Amtrak said Monday.
   The passengers aboard the California Zephyr remained on the
train, which still had light and heat, for several hours until a
work train Monday brought them here in two trips aboard seven
cabooses.
   ``We know what happened, not why it happened,'' said John
Jacobsen, Amtrak director of public relations in Washington, D.C.
   Jacobsen said some of the wheels slipped between the rails,
causing the cars to go off the tracks.
   ``The wheels dropped down between the rails and that's what kept
it upright,'' he said. ``The train couldn't move because it was
locked into place by the rail.''
   But, he emphasized, ``I don't know whether there was a problem
with the rail,'' and added that any number of things could have
caused the accident.
   ``That's all under investigation,'' he said.
   Rick Davis, Amtrak liaison for the Denver & Rio Grande Railroad,
which maintains the track, said it was premature to say what caused
the derailment.
   Jerry Pilcher of Chicago said passengers took the derailment in
stride, in part because the train already was several hours behind
schedule. ``There was a bit of caroling. It couldn't have gone more
smoothly if it had been a drill,'' said Pilcher.
   The train, carrying 294 passengers and about 15 crew members,
originated in Chicago and was headed for the West Coast. It was 150
miles west of Denver and 10 miles east of here when it left the
tracks Sunday night.
   It was snowing heavily at the time and about a foot of snow was
on the ground, but that shouldn't have had any bearing on the track,
Jacobsen said.
   Some passengers compared the derailment to a rough airplane
landing or driving over cobblestones.
   ``It was a miracle no one got hurt,'' said Wardell Copeland of
Vallejo, Calif. ``It was amazing that none of the cars went off into
the (Colorado) river. About 15 feet and that would have been it.''
   ``I was asleep and all at once ... I thought we were going over a
bridge,'' said Carolyn Johnson of Lincoln Neb. ``It just got real
rough and the train stopped.''
   Up to 40 Denver & Rio Grande maintenance crew members worked on
the grounded train Monday trying to get it back on the track but
said it could take until Tuesday. The railroad maintains the track
on which the Zephyr was traveling.
   Most passengers took buses to Salt Lake City or back to Denver.
   Jacobsen said the damage to the train was probably minor.
   An Amtrak derailment in Colorado in 1985 sent 26 people to the
hospital. Seven cars left the track in a canyon near Granby,
northwest of Denver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881226-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 2249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dole-Labor     12-26 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole-Labor,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Says Labor Department Should Take Leading Role on Child Care
Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALISBURY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Hanford Dole, President-elect
Bush's choice to be Labor Secretary, said Monday the department
would take a leadership role on the issue of child care.
   ``Women with children need help with child care so they can
work,'' she said. ``We have a changing work force and we have to be
sure we anticipate what the needs will be and be sure that training
is provided.''
   She said she also was interested in a wide range of other issues,
including ``continuing education, eliminating illiteracy,
discrimination, the fairness issue, safety, pensions _ you just go
through a whole range of issues.''
   ``It will be a real opportunity to be involved with helping the
inner-city poor,'' Mrs. Dole said in an interview with the Salisbury
Post. ``But the main thing will be to protect the welfare of working
men and women _ the working family _ and establish policies that
will really provide an opportunity for employment. I'm very much
oriented to helping people get a job and improve their working
lives.''
   She said the Cabinet position would give her a chance to make a
difference in the education and training of young people so they'll
have the skills they need in later years.
   ``The work force has changed and it will change more,'' Mrs. Dole
said. ``And young people will have to be sure their skills match the
needs.''
   Mrs. Dole, a Harvard-educated lawyer who served as transportation
secretary during the Reagan administration, said she and Bush had
discussed her areas of interests for several weeks before he offered
the job Thursday.
   ``He had ... told me he'd like to have me in his administration,
and I had described to him what I was thinking of doing outside of
government,'' she said.
   Mrs. Dole said she had set up a number of speaking engagements
and had several job offers from corporate boards and law firms.
   ``But my feeling was the centerpiece of my life was where I could
really make a difference to people, in helping to relieve some of
the most pressing needs,'' she said.
   The North Carolina native left her post as transportation
secretary to work for the unsuccessful 1988 presidential campaign of
her husband, Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   In announcing her selection Saturday, Bush said the fact that
Mrs. Dole is married to the Senate minority leader played no role in
his decision, saying, ``This appointment stands on its merits.''
</TEXT>
