<2ND_LINE>AM-Mulroy Memorial,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Executive Recalled As Man of `Special Grace'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mulroy Profile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENLAWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Mulroy, who died in the Pan Am jet
crash in Scotland, was eulogized Sunday as a man of ``sincerity,
diplomacy, gentle dignity, kindness, special grace, and
intelligence'' at a memorial Mass.
   Michael McDonald, a friend of Mulroy's for 30 years, told a group
of 500 worshipers that Mulroy had been like a ``father, brother,
confessor, and guidance counselor'' to him over the many years of
their friendship.
   Mulroy, who was director of international communications for The
Associated Press, was flying home with his son Sean, his
daughter-in-law Ingrid, his sister Bridget Concannon, her husband,
Thomas, and their son Sean, all of whom died in the Wednesday crash.
   The Rev. Augustine Sheehan, the parish priest at the St. Francis
of Assisi Church in this Long Island community, described Mulroy as
``a true gentleman'' who was ``upright, honest, dignified,
respectful and considerate of others.''
   Mulroy had spent 25 years with Pan American World Airways before
joining the AP in August 1984.
   The 59-year-old naturalized U.S. citizen was born near Cloongee,
Ireland, where he vacationed each summer.
   Among those attending the service were AP communications
executives who had flown in from London and Frankfurt, West Germany.
