<1ST_LINE>u a AM-StormRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0628 12-26 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Storm Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0628,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Socks Upper Midwest, Plains With Snow, Biting Cold</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with power outage in South
Dakota, avalanche warnings in Utah, United canceling flights at
O'Hare in Chicago, picks up 10th graf, pvs, `The storm kept...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By POLLY ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm bearing up to 12 inches of snow and wind chills as low as
45 degrees below moved through the Plains and Midwest on Monday,
closing highways and backing up air traffic just as holiday
travelers were heading home.
   ``Everything around here is in bad shape because of the weather,
and it's getting worse by the minute,'' said Ray Noll, a reserve
officer with the Porter County, Ind., sheriff's department. At least
25 cars were involved in a pile-up on an interstate highway in the
northern Indiana county, police said.
   Another pile-up of as many as 30 cars was reported in Indiana's
northeast county of Porter when a propane tanker overturned on
Interstate 65 Monday morning, state police said.
   Snow fell or was in the forecast from the Rockies and upper
Plains as far east as Ohio. Accidents and blowing snow closed
segments of interstate highways in several states, including Utah,
Minnesota, Indiana and South Dakota.
   Up to 12 inches were forecast in Minnesota and 10 inches in South
Dakota by Tuesday.
   ``We got a report that the weather was going to turn bad, and we
decided to leave a couple of days earlier than we intended to,''
said Vic Waters of Viroqua, Wis., who was heading east from Sioux
Falls, S.D. ``We found the roads were looking like we probably made
the right decision.''
   The storm knocked out power to more than 50,000 homes and
businesses in eastern South Dakota Monday afternoon for about two
hours when high winds caused power lines to bang together and
short-circuit, said a spokesman for Northern States Power Co.
   The snow caused delays of at least 30 minutes for planes taking
off and landing at Chicago's busy O'Hare International Airport, said
a Federal Aviation Administration duty officer who wouldn't give her
name.
   United cancelled all of its flights O'Hare on Monday afternoon,
said spokesman Rob Doughty. It was not known how many flights were
affected but on normal day, United has 400 departures from O'Hare,
he said.
   Wind chill readings fell to 45 degrees below zero in Jamestown,
N.D., Livingston, Mont., Douglas, Wyo., and Rapid City, S.D.
   It was the same storm system that earlier brought up to 2 feet or
more of snow in the West, with the mountains of Utah and Colorado
particularly hard hit. Powder Mountain, Utah, reported 26 inches of
snow.
   In Durango, Colo., two men were hospitalized in good condition
Monday after being buried under snow for nearly seven hours. They
were rescued by passers-by who heard their screams. The area was
under an avalanche warning.
   In Utah, officials warned of avalanches in mountains and Wasatch
Front after 8 inches of snow were forecast for the areas.
Authorities warned that large, spontaneous avalanches were likely on
all slopes above 7,000 feet elevation.
   The storm kept Utah Department of Transportation crews busy
Sunday, and at least one section of Interstate 84 was closed Monday
because of drifting snow.
   ``I don't know that any of them (crew members) were home for
Christmas,'' said Lynn Millard, a maintenance supervisor for the
department.
   Mountain areas of Arizona reported 2 to 5 inches of snow Sunday
evening to Monday morning, while parts of Montana got up to 8 inches
in the same period.
   Warroad, Minn., had the nation's low temperature Monday morning _
21 degrees below zero even before the wind chill was factored in. It
was 18 below at Cut Bank, Mont., and 14 below zero at Lovelock,
Nev., and Butte, Mont.
   Parts of Montana remained below zero during the day.
   By midday Monday, portions of Minnesota, Wisconsin, Iowa and
Illinois were getting snow at a rate of 2 inches an hour and had 8
inches by early afternoon. The western suburbs of Chicago had 7
inches of snow.
   ``If I could, I'd stay home and watch the football game today,''
said Rockford police Sgt. Colin Anderson.
   Snow, sleet and freezing rain were reported in Missouri and
elsewhere in Illinois.
   ``We're getting a lot of cars skidding out and sliding off the
roads,'' said Sgt. Malcolm Burnett of the Illinois State Police
office in Springfield. ``We've got snow and sleet in the north and
freezing rain further south.''
   ``They've forgotten how to drive on this stuff,'' said Lt. Ralph
Henson of the Illinois State Police station in Ashkum in the
east-central part of the state, where about 15 accidents were
reported in the first hour of snowfall.
   The cold extended all the way to the West Coast. San Francisco
had a non-official low of 27 in Golden Gate Park, and three bridges
northeast of Oakland closed because of ice on the road, officials
said.
</TEXT>
