<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak says he is willing to
go to Israel _ if it would help bring peace to the Middle East _ in
what would be the first trip to Israel by an Arab leader since Anwar
Sadat's daring 1977 visit.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel said he would welcome a
visit.
   Mubarak made the offer in two weekend interviews. However, he
told the Tokyo newspaper Yomiuri on Sunday that he would go only if
Israel extends the invitation unconditionally. ``I don't accept any
preconditions,'' he said.
   In responding to Mubarak's initial offer, made through an
interview with the Kuwait newspaper Al-Anbaa, Shamir said Sunday
that he would be ``very happy to receive him in Israel.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In Christmas messages, world and spiritual leaders urged a new
surge of generosity to help heal the wounds of people whose lives
have been shattered by the Armenian earthquake, the Pan Am crash in
Scotland and the AIDS plague.
   ``Our hearts and prayers go out to those who have been injured
and bereaved and it is my hope that the eternal message of Christmas
will bring some comfort in the hour of sadness,'' Queen Elizabeth II
said in an unprecedented update of her annual Christmas message.
   In Bethlehem, the hilltop town in the Israeli-occupied West Bank
where Jesus was born, steady rain and the yearlong Palestinian
uprising dissuaded crowds of pilgrims from celebrating Sunday's
holiday.
   Several hundred people chanted Mass in the Church of the Nativity
while Israeli soldiers chased stone-throwing youths in the town's
streets. In the occupied lands, one Palestinian was killed and 16
were reported wounded in clashes with Israeli troops. Arab reports
said a second Palestinian died of wounds suffered in an earlier
clash.
   Pope John Paul II set the tone of compassion for the holiday in
offering his Christmas wish: that ``science and love'' would find a
cure for the deadly scourge of AIDS.
   In Armenia, President-elect Bush's son, John, and grandson,
George, toured the disaster area and passed out candy bars and games
to injured children at a hospital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vice-chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee says the possible presence of a CIA operative on the Pan
Am jet that crashed last week probably would not, by itself, have
provoked a terrorist attack.
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said Sunday on ABC's ``This Week
With David Brinkley'' that he could not confirm whether the CIA
agent had been on the flight.
   But Cohen said that even if the agent had been aboard it would
not necessarily be significant because terrorists ``could have
eliminated him'' by direct assassination on the ground.
   ``I don't think you can draw any connection one way or another at
this point,'' Cohen said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEEVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This farm town is unaccustomed to being in
the national spotlight, but all that could change because a
10,000-acre spread in ``God's country'' is a favorite hunting spot
of President-elect Bush.
   The president-elect today was to begin a four-day visit to Will
Farish's Lazy F Ranch. For the past 20 Christmas seasons, Bush has
retreated there to tote a shotgun through the South Texas mesquite
in search of quail and other game birds.
   Nobody paid much attention until the vice president became the
president-elect. And some in this town of 15,000 are applauding the
change.
   ``It would bring a lot of tourists to town,'' said Janice Porter,
manager of the Beeville Chamber of Commerce. ``It would do a lot for
Beeville.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush's choice to lead the
Defense Department says an emphasis on weapons systems that depend
on fewer people may help the Pentagon meet its needs in a time of
budgetary constraint.
   ``The big cost is not in the B-2 (bomber), the B-1 and the
aircraft carriers,'' former Texas Sen. John Tower said Sunday. ``The
big cost is not in the hardware, the big cost is in personnel.''
   Tower, Bush's designated defense secretary, said one of his first
priorities would be devising a strategy to achieve national
objectives for defense.
   ``Then we have to look at the roles and missions of all our
forces and see where they fit into that strategy,'' he said on the
CBS-TV program ``Face the Nation.''
