<DOCNO> AP881226-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek ADV08   12-26 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, ADV 08,0834</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Jan. 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Game show host Pat Sajak is starting a new
late-night talk show on CBS this week, but he's not bragging that
he's taking on Johnny Carson head-on.
   Neither Sajak nor CBS want to oversell the show the way the
syndicated ``Thicke of the Night'' was trumpeted in 1983.
   ``We don't want that kind of pre-show hype because there's no way
you can live up to it,'' Sajak says. ``We want people to know we're
coming, but we don't want to build up expectations.''
   Sajak says his exposure as host of ``Wheel of Fortune'' will
help. ``People know me. That's half the battle.''
   Sajak has quit the daytime version of ``Wheel of Fortune'' on
NBC, but will continue as host of the nighttime show, the
highest-rated show in syndication.
   ``The Pat Sajak Show'' makes its debut on CBS on Monday, putting
the network back into the talk show business for the first time
since it canceled Merv Griffin in 1972. It was Griffin, who as
producer of ``Wheel of Fortune,'' lifted Sajak, a former TV
weatherman, out of obscurity.
   ``I've always wanted to do late-night television,'' Sajak says.
``That's a pretty narrow thing to aim for. It only took 30 years.''
   CBS turned again to a talk show to try to recoup its late-night
losses. More than a fourth of its affiliate stations deserted the
network's rotating action-adventure shows. But announcement of the
Sajak show has brought most of the defecting stations back.
Apparently 90 percent of the CBS stations will broadcast the show.
   It looks like a renewal of the old talk show wars, when Griffin
on CBS and Dick Cavett on ABC, plus David Frost and Mike Douglas in
syndication, took on Carson. Now, besides Sajak, Joan Rivers and
Arsenio Hall are joining the fray with new syndicated talk shows.
   But this time each show is looking to find its own niche and
audience. Taking on Carson head-on, or even appearing to, as
``Thicke of the Night'' and Joan Rivers tried, is an invitation to
disaster.
   ``We have great respect for Johnny, but we don't plan our show
around him,'' Sajak says. ``I think CBS has realistic expectations.
They don't think we have to knock someone off to be a success.
Actuall, Johnny's been very gracious to me. He once asked me to be a
guest host.''
   Sajak will find himself competing not only against Carson, but
against the first half of NBC's ``Late Night with David Letterman.''
His new show will be 90 minutes, while Carson has long since had his
show cut to an hour. ``When you get going you want to be there as
much as you can,'' Sajak says.
   Once Sajak got the go-ahead from CBS one of the first things he
did was talk to others who had attempted talk shows and failed.
   ``The one thing we kept hearing was that too many chiefs, too
many vice presidents, too many executive producers were running
around giving orders,'' he says. ``Everybody had ideas and the host
was forced to squeeze them all in.
   ``So, we're going to keep it simple. There's just myself and the
producer, Paul Gilbert. We basically make the decisions. CBS has had
the courage of its convictions. Too often going on TV is like a
marriage. You marry someone because you love them, then spend the
next five years trying to change them. I am very wary of network
interference.''
   Sajak, who concedes he is a traditionalist, says he is baffled by
some of the changes in television _ particularly the turn taken by
afternoon talk shows.
   ``I don't know what to make of all this chair-throwing and trash
TV,'' he says. ``I hope it's just a passing fad.''
   He cautions viewers against expecting anything radical. He will
not be different just for the sake of being different.
   ``You make it different by bringing your own personality to it,''
he says. ``It's `The Pat Sajak Show.' That's the only talent I have,
being Pat Sajak. The reason so few people have succeeded in this is
that they feel they should always be in the spotlight and get all
the laughs. You have to step aside and let your guests shine. When
your guests look good, you look good.''
   Sajak recalls that as a youngster he frequently climbed out of
bed late at night to watch Jack Paar, who was host of ``The Tonight
Show'' before Carson.
   ``I was at Jack's house in Connecticut recently,'' he says. ``It
was fun to hear the old stories, get some advice, look at some old
tapes and relive the past a little.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
