<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 1309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV08   12-26 0978</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 08,1000</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taped to the mirror in David Dukes' dressing room
at the Eugene O'Neill Theater are several pieces of white paper
filled with scribbles. They are his lifeline to understanding the
plot of ``M. Butterfly.''
   But the jottings don't even tell the entire story of the complex
and fascinating play. The actor says the scrawl pertains just to
``my action'' _ what his character goes through, scene by scene, in
this Tony award-winning Broadway hit about a bizarre, 20-year love
affair between a French diplomat and a Chinese opera singer who
turns out to be a man.
   ``It's the only way I can keep the whole play in my mind,'' says
Dukes, who portrays the deluded, desperate diplomat. ``If things
start to go wrong on stage, I'll just stare at the paper for a while
and try to track the character's development again. It's very easy
in a long run to go in directions that you're not quite aware of and
eventually find you're getting too serious or too comic or
whatever.''
   For Dukes, a highly verbal, intense and quick-witted actor, the
role has brought high praise, including cheers from New York theater
critics who came back to see the play after he replaced its original
star, John Lithgow.
   You could describe the 43-year-old Dukes as ``one of those New
York theater actors who always works'' except that he happens to
live in California and works all over television and movies too.
   TV audiences know him from a slew of miniseries: ``Space,''
``Kane and Abel,'' ``George Washington,'' and most recently, ``The
Winds of War'' and ``War and Remembrance,'' in which he played
Leslie Slote.
   Broadway theatergoers might remember him from runs in ``Bent''
and as part of the replacement casts in ``Amadeus'' and ``Dracula.''
Dukes took over from Lithgow in ``M. Butterfly'' last August after
only two weeks of rehearsal. But it's easier, he says, going into a
play that already is running. In fact, he watches his predecessors
for tips.
   ``I believe in selective theft,'' Dukes says with a grin.
``There's a great advantage coming in and replacing somebody. You
get to see the whole thing. John Lithgow, until he saw my dress
rehearsal, never did get to see the whole production.''
   Dukes also talked extensively with Lithgow, who is an old friend,
about the role. The conversations were invaluable.
   John Dexter, the director, was ill and couldn't attend Dukes'
rehearsals. So Stuart Ostrow, the show's producer, and the stage
manager acted as his director. Lithgow also watched Dukes' last
dress-technical rehearsal and used the occasion to tell his
successor everything about the role that Dexter had told him.
   Lithgow's most specific advice?
   ``Remember the music of the play,'' Dukes recalls. ``The speeches
do have a musical tone to them.''
   Ask Dukes for a description of the character he plays, and he'll
quickly say, ``a dork _ an unromantic male who is lucky to have a
wife.
   ``At the same time, the diplomat serves as the narrator of the
play and must tell the story with confidence and assuredness,''
Dukes adds. ``There are a lot of strange, conflicting colors in this
play.''
   To conserve his energy for the marathon that is ``M. Butterfly,''
Dukes hibernates much of the day. He'll do voice-over auditions for
television commercials, since they don't require much physical
effort, but not much else.
   ``There's no way around the fact,'' he says. ``This role does you
in.'' That's why he signed only for a six-month run and is eager to
get home to California and his wife and 5-year-old daughter. His
wife, Carol Muske, teaches at the University of South California and
has a novel, ``Dear Digby,'' coming out in April.
   Still, Dukes will usually go anywhere for a good acting job. That
passion wasn't always there. It wasn't until Dukes did a play his
senior year in high school in Marin County, Calif., that he wanted
to become an actor. He went to college as a math major, but by the
end of his freshman year had switched to speech and drama because
``girls like actors much more than they like mathematicians.''
   After graduating from college, Dukes acted and worked behind the
scenes at the American Conservatory Theater in San Francisco, and
never looked back. For ACT and touring companies that came through
San Francisco, he also worked as a stagehand.
   Dukes began jumping from repertory company to repertory company,
working for the Alley Theater in Houston, the San Diego Shakespeare
Festival, the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles, and then the Charles
Street Playhouse in Boston.
   In 1971, Dukes received his first New York show, a revival of
Moliere's ``A School for Wives,'' with Brian Bedford and Joan Van
Ark. It turned into a hit and later toured the country, making his
name known in New York.
   ``Theater work is what I think I do best,'' he says. ``When I
step on a stage, it's a world I know. Cameras and me are not close
friends.
   ``But you've got to do television and film. If I had done more of
it, perhaps they would have asked me to originate this role in `M.
Butterfly,''' Dukes adds. ``Yet I've never burned to be a star. You
have to have enough of a name to get the big parts with the best
people.
   ``I'm also one of those faces, because I change my look for jobs,
that people will look at and say, `Didn't I go to college with you
in Virginia?' I go through that a lot. They think they know me, but
they can't remember where.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
