<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   12-26 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,0843</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: CH is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Bagdad Cafe,'' ``Candy Mountain,''
``Rikky and Pete''
   
   ``Bagdad Cafe'' (Virgin Vision; VHS-Beta, $79.95; Rated PG)
   
   Eleonore and Percy Adlon, a couple of German filmmakers, fell in
love with the wacky desert light in Bagdad, a defunct town outside
Barstow, Calif. They made a movie about lovable eccentrics who
inhabit a roadside truckstop.
   It's lovely to see the desert light and watch tractor-trailer
rigs hiss by at dusk like the tide, but then there's the rest of
this awkward, conventional, stolidly Germanic film with which to
contend.
   Marianne Sagebrecht plays the plump hausfrau Jasmin who is
stranded at the cafe run by Brenda (CH Pounder), whose slightly
crazed, unfocused rage is unsettling. Jack Palance as a painter is
still Jack Palance.
   This slight, smarmy movie got big mileage at the art houses for
reasons that mystify. It's reminiscent of the Brazilian comedy
``Altemira,'' which had more important things to say about travel,
misfits and entertainment.
   ``Bagdad Cafe'' tries to create an engaging artificiality in that
truckstop's unforgiving desert light. If they'd used a sound stage,
it might have worked. As it is, the desert wins hands down. Trucker,
pass by.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Candy Mountain'' (Republic Pictures Home Video; VHS, $79.95;
Rated R)
   
   Who can resist a subtle, little, too-hip road movie that casts
Tom Waits as a wealthy golf fanatic, Leon Redbone as a Canadian
constable with a jail in his basement, Joe Strummer (The Clash) as a
fascist security guard and Dr. John as a henpecked mobile-home
dweller?
   ``Candy Mountain'' played only briefly in a few art houses, so
the appearance of the video is a service to film buffs in
medium-to-small media markets everywhere. Kevin J. O'Connor stars as
Julius, a bone-headed guitar picker intent on jiving his way into
the big time. When he plays backup _ for free _ for big-timer Keith
Burns (David Johansen), Burns is moved to yell in his face,
``Ba-BOM, ba-BOM, ba-BOM, ba-BOM. Ya got that?''
   Julius, wising to the fact that Burns and some record company
execs are obsessed with finding the fabled Elmore Silk (Harris
Yulin), lies and says he knows him. Silk, it seems, was something of
a guru to the rock world as maker of the world's best guitars, but
he disappeared. No one knows where or why. Now his guitars are worth
thousands of dollars apiece.
   Thus begins Julius' quest to find the master and lure him back
into the financial fold, thereby, in Julius' mind, assuring himself
a record deal.
   Julius careens through the debris of Elmore's past before finding
the master at what seems to be literally the end of the Earth.
   Directed by underground filmmaker Robert Frank, this is a movie
that works on a lot of different levels, and the end is stunning.
   _ By Kathryn Baker, AP Television Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Rikky and Pete'' (CBS-Fox Video; VHS-Beta, $79.97; Rated R)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   In ``Rikky and Pete,'' they get the car chase scene over early,
leaving a few wrecks but moving on to a charming and funny movie
about how two intelligent Australian misfits try to find their place
in the world.
   Rikky (Nina Landis) is a geologist who moonlights as a folk
singer. Her brother, Pete (Stephen Kearney), is a talented inventor
unable to hold a regular job, enraging his stuffy, wealthy father by
working as a paperboy and using an ingenious mechanical folder on
his rounds.
   They both feel out of place in Melbourne, and when Pete has a
serious run-in with the police sergeant who crippled their mother in
a car accident, they escape to the outback.
   They find people and work they like in a mining town full of
eccentric characters. Rikki sings, they both find romance and they
strike it rich in their own mine _ that is, until the arrival of
their parents and the sergeant.
   Director Nadia Tass has a great cast, including Landis and
Kearney, as well as Filipino actor Tetchie Agbayane as Pete's love
interest. ``Rikky and Pete'' is light and fun, easily able to cheer
up an evening with the VCR.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
