<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   12-26 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,0516</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``California Roll'' (CBS) _ Osamu
   
   East is East and West is West, right?
   Not according to Japanese composer and musician Osamu, who's
successfully blended traditional Oriental rhythms with faster-paced
jazz and rock on ``California Roll.''
   For Western music lovers who've heard some pleasing Eastern tunes
but don't know what to buy at the record store, ``California Roll''
is an ideal, aurally palatable introduction.
   The album, which is Osamu Kitajima's third in the United States,
is a showcase for the Chinese koto, a 13-string zither-like
instrument that emits the precise, delicate sound familiar to
Westerners as ``Oriental music.''
   But don't get the idea that ``California Roll'' is nothing but
inscrutable meandering. It's too full of state-of-the-art
electronics for that.
   Osamu plays all the instruments on four of the nine songs that
feature the koto surrounded by a patter of percussion, bells and
synthesized sounds.
   Songs such as ``Escape Space,'' ``Back Street to Paradise'' and
``White in Flight,'' with their sensitive melodies and
slower-than-slow rhythms, lend a sensation of limbo-like suspension
to the listener. (They also wouldn't sound out of place on a ``Miami
Vice'' soundtrack.)
   Osamu can rip out a hot rock guitar lick as well. On ``Leading
Edge,'' the guitar stakes out the melody, followed by a bridge on
the koto. ``Eastern Eyes, Western Skies'' features an extended
guitar solo, as does the even harder-rocking ``Samurai Lover.''
   The title of ``California Roll'' refers to an American version of
that Japanese favorite, sushi. Osamu's musical synthesis gives
Western ears a taste of that country's sonic delicacy.
   _ By Curt Anderson, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Big Time'' (Island) _ Tom Waits
   
   Much of Tom Waits' music is difficult, but ``Big Time'' is
impossible. The poor sound quality makes it that way.
   ``Big Time,'' released in conjunction with the concert film of
the same name, contains live performances of songs from Waits' three
most recent studio albums _ ``Swordfishtrombone,'' ``Rain Dogs'' and
``Franks Wild Years.'' Fans already familiar with the material may
find ``Big Time'' of interest. But the uninitiated likely will be
frustrated by the task of trying to decipher Waits' lyrics.
   When his gravel-coated voice isn't too far from the mike, it's
too close. And on three songs that were mixed live to cassette, the
singing is overwhelmed by tape hiss. It's too bad, because the
enigmatic Waits is clever with words. A lyric sheet would have
helped, but Waits' five-piece backup band is mired in aural muck,
too.
   There are times when sound quality that is less than
state-of-the-art enhances a performance _ Bruce Springsteen's
``Nebraska'' album comes to mind. And Waits, last of the beatniks,
is anything but a digital performer. But the small-time sound on
``Big Time'' causes the medium to block the message.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
