<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Russell ADV06-08   12-26 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Russell, ADV 06-08,0890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06-08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Jan 6-8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Basketball Coach Inspires Kurt Russell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When baseball stars Mickey Mantle and Roger Maris
made the movie ``Follow Me Home'' in the early 1960s, they inspired
a young Kurt Russell to take up acting.
   Twenty-five years later, he drew upon another sports figure in
preparing for his role in ``Tequila Sunrise.'' Russell, who stars
with Mel Gibson and Michelle Pfeiffer, decided that Los Angeles
Lakers coach Pat Riley had the kind of look his part required, a
look the actor describes as ``relaxed GQ.''
   ``There are very few men that have the confidence to wear ... an
outrageous fashion statement,'' said Russell, who emulates Riley's
slicked-back hair and well-tailored suits in the movie.
   ``I felt that Pat Riley's look was right for this film because he
was arrogantly confident but not offensive. It's very tough to do
that.''
   Russell plays a police officer investigating a drug dealer who is
also an old high school friend (Gibson), and who is involved with a
mysterious Mexican drug lord (Raul Julia). Russell seduces Pfeiffer,
the owner of a fashionable restaurant and Gibson's friend, and uses
her to extract information on the drug dealer.
   ``I feel good about the chemistry of Michelle and myself and
Mel,'' Russell said. ``It reminded me of doing `Silkwood' with Meryl
(Streep) and Cher. I always felt there were three specific people in
the room and they each in a good way brought something to the
other.''
   Russell emerges as a negative character in ``Tequila Sunrise''
because he manipulates both Gibson and Pfeiffer for his own ends.
However, the actor enjoyed his role.
   ``I like the style of some of those old gangster movies that
(James) Cagney did. You didn't pull for him, but you did feel bad
when he got killed off. Cagney played the worst guy in the room; I
was drawn to that character,'' he said.
   Russell, a child star in Disney movies (``Follow Me, Boys,''
``The Computer Wore Tennis Shoes,'' ``The Fox and the Hound''), has
a long history of playing bad guys.
   ``A lot of people take Walt Disney and lump it all together. The
first picture I did, I was the tough kid on the block. My father was
an alcoholic and I was sling-shotting everybody,'' he said.
   Russell's career sagged through most of the 1970s until he landed
the starring role in the television movie ``Elvis.'' It was, Russell
admitted, a nearly impossible task.
   ``Elvis Presley is the second most recognizable unit to
Coca-Cola. The only thing tougher to do is play the Coca-Cola
logo,'' he said.
   But Russell managed to receive surprisingly positive reviews and
has gone on to be one of the most popular actors of the '80s,
appearing in ``Silkwood,'' and ``Used Cars'' among other films.
   With that popularity has come success. How does he handle it?
   ``Failure is quite easy to deal with because it's right there and
it's much less complex than success,'' the actor said. ``Success can
become very complex, dealing with your ego and dealing with greed.
You begin to make amounts of money you don't want to stop making.''
   Money has freed him, though, to enjoy more private time. In 1983,
he fell in love with actress Goldie Hawn while they were making
``Swing Shift.'' They have houses in California and Colorado. Hawn
was an old friend of ``Tequila Sunrise'' writer-director Robert
Towne.
   ``I find Robert Towne's style inexplicibly hypnotic,'' Russell
said of the screenwriter of ``The Last Detail'' and ``Chinatown.''
   ``He makes you keep turning the pages. You're not exactly sure
why. I feel that way about Bob Towne as a human being as well.''
   Russell, the son of TV actor Bing Russell, grew up in Southern
California. In 1963, at the age of 12, he made his film debut in the
Elvis Presley movie ``It Happened at the World's Fair.''
   But he loved sports more than acting, and spent some time playing
minor league baseball for the San Diego Padres and California
Angels. A shoulder injury suffered at age 22 ended his baseball
career. Sports continues to pop up in Russell's conversation,
especially when he makes comparisons to acting.
   ``Acting's the easiest job in the world,'' he said. ``I am
accused of not liking actors. I do like them, but they think
somebody interfering with their ever important performance is an
obstacle.
   ``They haven't faced Nolan Ryan with the winning run on third
base, that's an obstacle. Or face Mike Ditka with four yards to go,
there's an obstacle that's tough to get around.
   ``I watched a guy drilling in the street and he comes to this
point where he gets into this stuff that's heavy concrete. This guy
had an obstacle!''
   Russell brings an athlete's sense of concentration to his work.
   ``You must get zeroed in; nothing else exists when you're doing
it,'' Russell explained. ``I would like to think if I'm on this
jackhammer or getting across the goal line, it would be the same
way.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions Jan 6-8</NOTE>
</DOC>
