<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Warnke ADV06-08   12-26 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Warnke, ADV 06-08,0720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06-08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 6-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Part Comic, Part Evangelist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Warnke is one of a kind _ he's part
evangelist and part stand-up comic. Or, as some folks say, he's ``a
standup Jimmy Swaggart with long hair.''
   The 43-year-old Christian humorist and recording artist, who has
shoulder-length locks, is also a former heroin addict and satanist
high priest who once had more than 1,500 worshippers.
   Noting his background, he says: ``If God can use me, he can use
anybody.''
   He shares his religious faith at up to 22 personal appearances a
month. He's just released his 12th humor album, ``One in a
Million,'' on DaySpring Records of Nashville.
   He employs 30 people at his ministry office in Burgin, Ky., where
he has noted a marked rise in telephone calls from people, including
the police, asking about the occult.
   ``There's been a dramatic increase in the past three years,'' he
said in a telephone interview. ``We're seeing younger kids getting
involved. It used to be people age 20, but now it's 13 and 14. I'd
say 70 percent of the calls deal with the occult. This is a
frightening trend.''
   Warnke, who wrote the 1972 book ``The Satan Seller,'' which has
sold more than 3 million copies, believes there's a definite link
between the occult and heavy metal music.
   ``We've never investigated a case with the police where heavy
metal was not a factor. The music drives the lyrics into the
conscious and subconscious. Then there's the clothing, the attitudes
of the musicians, the things they say and the lifestyles they
purport, and the symbols.''
   The symbols include demonic-looking caricatures, horns worn on
heads and upside down crosses.
   He compares music to lumber in that either can be used for good
purposes or otherwise. ``If you put a 2-by-4 in the hands of the Ku
Klux Klan, it's bad. But in the hands of a carpenter, it's not.''
   Warnke, who has been featured on the TV show ``20-20,'' says he
began his involvement with the occult at age 12 or 13. He joined a
coven in the early 1960s when he was in college and became a
satanist high priest.
   ``I was the star sinner on campus,'' he recalled.
   He used heroin heavily. And some of his satanic followers tried
to murder him by injecting him with an overdose of heroin and
leaving him on the streets of San Bernadino, Calif., to die.
   Passers-by saw him and took him to a hospital, where his recovery
began.
   ``If I'd have had to kick it (addiction) in the streets, I'd have
been dead for sure,'' Warnke said.
   He later joined the Navy and served one tour of duty in Vietnam.
He became a Christian and devoted himself to preaching against
satanism.
   After his records started coming out, Record World magazine
honored him as the contemporary and inspirational non-musical artist
of the year, 1976-79.
   He estimates he speaks to more than 1 million people a year. He
has performed for the queen of Denmark and the king of Sweden and
been to Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Canada.
   He's drafting a sequel to ``The Satan Seller'' that is due out
soon.
   ``I've never been a perfect Christian,'' Warnke said. ``That's
where I deviate from others who seem to have a mandate to tell
everyone else how to live. Jesus has been a perfect Jesus, and I
just try to spend time talking about him and not me.
   ``What I'm trying to put across to Christians is that you don't
have to be stereotypical. The Lord will use you no matter who you
are. For people who don't know Jesus, we hope they see him and get
saved.''
   Warnke, a native of Evansville, Ind., said threats against his
life picked up after he began working with police on cases involving
satanism.
   ``The threats used to be just rhetoric. But people have jumped on
stage with knives and I've been shot at backstage. I just keep
ducking,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions Jan. 6-8</NOTE>
