<HEAD>Beepers Becoming A Problem In Many Major Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The persistent beeping of pocket pagers has become
too common in many big hospitals, taking doctors away from their
patients to deal with questions that are not really urgent, a new
study concludes.
   Beepers have largely replaced overhead paging systems. Among the
most frequent targets of the beepers are interns, the young doctors
who provide much of the care in large hospitals.
   In a study at three hospitals affiliated with the University of
California, San Francisco, Drs. Mitchell H. Katz and Steven A.
Schroeder persuaded 26 interns to keep logs of their beeper calls.
   The interns were paged an average of once an hour. However, on 24
occasions, interns were paged five or more times an hour. One
unfortunate intern got eight calls in a single hour. The figures
probably underestimate the frequency of pages: some interns said
they had to stop keeping logs because they were too busy answering
pages.
   Only about one-third of the pages were for truly urgent matters
requiring immediate changes in patient care. Most concerned matters
that could have been put off until later. Some were entirely
unnecessary.
   For instance, one intern was beeped awake to evaluate a patient
whose mental status had changed.
   ``On arrival,'' the doctors wrote, ``the intern learned that the
patient appeared drowsy because he had been asleep, like the intern,
when the nurse evaluated him.''
   The doctors said recently in the New England Journal of Medicine
that a few changes, such as relying more on written notes and
grouping several non-urgent pages together, could reduce the paging
interruptions up to 42 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Yale Awarded $6.6 Million Grant For Schizophrenia Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Institute of Mental Health
has given Yale School of Medicine researchers $6.6 million to study
schizophrenia, which affects an estimated one person in 10 at some
point in life.
   Schizophrenia usually begins with an apparent personality change
that may include social withdrawal, difficulty in communicating and
lethargy. Later, in its more active phase, it can make victims see
hallucinations and hear voices.
   They may feel controlled by invisible agents or believe their
thoughts are being broadcast to others. They may adopt new
identities.
   The research will be guided by the concept that the mental
disorder rises from physical rather than purely psychological
problems, said Patricia S. Goldman-Rakic, a neuroscience professor
who will direct the study.
   ``The Center for Neuroscience Research underscores the modern
conception of the disease as having an organic basis that affects
the highest center of the brain, the cerebral cortex, where the
functions of perception, memory and thinking are carried out,''
Goldman-Rakic said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EPA Picks Pitt For Pollution-Control Development Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has
picked the University of Pittsburgh to open the nation's first
center to speed commercial development of pollution control
technology.
   U.S. industry and government spent nearly $80 billion in 1987 for
pollution controls, and the cost of cleaning hazardous waste sites
is estimated at more than $200 billion over the next 20 years, Pitt
said in a statement.
   The National Environmental Technology Applications Corporation
``will be a positive force for changing the way government and
industry work together in the environmental area,'' said EPA
Administrator Lee Thomas.
   Pitt President Wesley W. Posvar said, ``It is clear that to bring
environmental technology out of the laboratory and into the
marketplace with the approval of government, a strong public-private
sector partnership is required. NETAC will help forge that
partnership.''
   EPA and Pitt will each pay half of the center's operating
expenses of $9 million over its first three years. NETAC is expected
to be in operation within two years at the university's Applied
Research Center in Harmarville.
   The Federal Technology Transfer Act of 1986 encourages the
government and companies to cooperate in moving new technologies to
market.
   Pitt two years ago formed the Center for Hazardous Materials
Research, a non-profit organization that does $2.5 million a year in
business.
</TEXT>
