<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NewspaperRecycling Bjt   12-26 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspaper Recycling, Bjt,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandatory Recycling Creates A Glut Of Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINELAND, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small mountains of newspapers are
swallowing up Joseph Giordano's recycling yard, forcing him to post
a hand-printed sign:
   ``NOT ACCEPTING NEWSPAPER UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE!!''
   The small cardboard announcement is bad news for local
municipalities trying to comply with the state's mandatory recycling
laws, enacted in April 1987. The sign in Giordano's yard is
indicative of a newspaper glut in the recycling business.
   ``I'm limited in places where I can sell it,'' he said. ``I can't
sell newsprint to a tissue mill, because it's not a soft paper. All
overseas markets have put their orders on hold.''
   Aletha Spang, acting administrator in the state's Office of
Recycling, said ``Paper dealers warned us that this could happen.''
   ``Our feeling was that with a strong export market, there
wouldn't be a problem,'' she said.
   Foreign countries, especially in Asia, have traditionally
recycled U.S. newspapers into paperboard that may return to the
United States in the form of boxes for cameras and VCRs. But within
the past few months, the bottom has fallen out of the export market.
   ``The export market has gotten smart,'' Ms. Spang said. ``They
know the paper is going to come, regardless of what they have to
pay.''
   New Jersey, the first state to impose a mandatory recycling
program, in recent weeks has experienced the dilemma of what to do
with massive volumes of waste and not enough recycling facilities.
   ``You can mandate collection, but the state can't mandate making
it into a new product,'' Ms. Spang said. ``That's part of the
marketplace.''
   She tried to be optimistic, saying,``We're hoping this (glut) is
just temporary.''
   But Giordano was blunt about the prospects: ``These newspapers
are probably going to end up in the dump.''
   J. Rodney Edwards, vice president in charge of recycling for the
American Paper Institute in New York, said that while there is
mandatory collection of newspapers, it doesn't necessarily mean
mandatory recycling.
   ``The capacity to use all the newspapers we recycle is limited by
the number of recycling mills,'' he said.
   The mountains of old newspapers are getting so high that
municipalities may soon have to pay recyclers to take the papers
away, said James L. Burke, an executive vice president of Garden
State Paper.
   ``When mandatory recycling first came on line, people thought it
would be a money-making program for their towns,'' he said. ``But
the majority of paper collected from municipalities is of lower
quality than we get from volunteers _ it's filled with mailers,
gummed labels and other contaminants.''
   ``We have to put money and labor into cleaning it up, so we may
have to charge to take it,'' he said.
   Burke noted, however, it may still be cheaper for municipalities
to pay recycling companies to take the papers away.
   ``If tipping fees at the dump are $100 a ton, and we charge a
modest $10 a ton, we may still be a good deal,'' he said.
   John Haas, recycling coordinator for Ocean County, said most
newspapers are now sent to the Garden State plant at a profit, but
there are concerns about the future.
   ``We're noticing what's happening in other parts of the state,
and we're all affected by the same market forces,'' he said.
   Giordano called on state officials to deal with the problem.
   ``The states need to put more pressure on the mills to force them
to buy more recycling material and stop using fibers from trees and
plants,'' he said.
   ``The solid waste problem is economical, social and political,
and it's going to take good political leadership to address the
problem properly,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
