<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened slightly higher against the
Japanese yen Tuesday morning, and prices also edged up on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 124.80, up 0.08 yen from Monday's close of
124.72 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
181.65 points Monday, rose an additional 78.53 points or 0.26
percent, moving to 29,946.54 in the first 15 minutes of morning
trading.
   On Monday, the index closed at 29,868.01.
   Market players were in a wait-and-see mood because overseas
markets were closed Monday for the Christmas holiday, an analyst
with Nomura Securities said.
   ``There is no major movement in the market, but participants
might try to raise the index to end this year's trading at the
30,000-point mark,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The market went above the 30,000-point level for the first time
Dec. 7, closing at 30,050.82, but slipped lower on profit-taking the
next day.
   In the currency market, traders also stayed on the sidelines
following Monday's Christmas holiday, dealers said.
   Market players were unlikely to make major moves before the New
York market opened later Tuesday, a dealer at a commercial bank in
Tokyo said, speaking on condition he not be named.
</TEXT>
